<HEADLINE> Dawn-To-Dusk General Strike Passed Off Peacefully in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA , August 30 (Xinhua) -- A dawn-to-dusk countrywide
general strike called by the Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP)-
led four-party opposition alliance protesting price hike of gas
and petroleum products, Wednesday paralyzed normal life in the
country, but passed off peacefully.
</P>
<P>
No major disturbances were reported during the striking hours
except a few stray incidents.
</P>
<P>
Police and eyewitnesses said five persons were wounded by
homemade bombs during a clash between strikers and pro-government
activists in the capital. The violence erupted when about 300
opposition demonstrators were challenged by their rivals. "They
hurled bombs at each other. At least five persons were injured,"
said a police officer in the scene.
</P>
<P>
Normal life in the capital was paralyzed as transport service
went off the roads, but paddle rickshaws were as usual in the
streets.
</P>
<P>
The strike, the second in a week, disrupted banking sector and
shut schools and colleges and many offices in the country.
</P>
<P>
The BNP and its allies-- Jatiya Party, Jamaat-e-Islami and
Islamic Oikya Jote (IOJ), called the strike to protest against the
price hike of petroleum products and gas.
</P>
<P>
The government recently raised the prices of petroleum products
by 13 per cent and gas tax by 15 per cent. The opposition claimed
that the government raised the prices to ruin the economy, saying
the price hike will have a far reaching negative impact on the
cost of power, fertilizer, industrial and agricultural products
and above all, the cost of living. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
