<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parliament Seat of Bangladeshi Former President Vacated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The parliament seat of former
President and Jatiya Party Chairman H.M. Ershad was Wednesday
declared vacant following his conviction in a corruption case.
</P>
<P>
A parliament secretariat notification ordered vacating the
parliament seat of Ershad with retrospective effect from the date
of High Court verdict upholding his conviction.
</P>
<P>
The parliament secretariat said Ershad was found guilty in a
corruption case by the higher court that sentenced him to five
years' imprisonment on August 24.
</P>
<P>
"As per Article 66 (2) of the Constitution, Ershad is no more
eligible to remain as parliament member and the seat will fall
vacant from the date of the pronouncement of the verdict," the
notification said.
</P>
<P>
Ershad termed the notification of Parliament Secretariat as
illegal in a sharp reaction.
</P>
<P>
"It is illegal. Nobody can cancel my seat," said the former
President.
</P>
<P>
His counsel Barrister Rafiqul Huq, a former attorney general,
also termed the action of the parliament secretariat unseating
Ershad from the parliament as illegal.
</P>
<P>
"Parliament secretariat has no power to declare vacant the seat
of Ershad in Parliament. The case in question has not reached its
finality. A leave petition to move the Supreme Court against the
verdict of the High Court has already been filed," said the
counsel.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Article 66 (4) of the Constitution that says any
dispute over the parliament seat shall be referred to the Election
Commission to hear and determine, the counsel viewed that the
matter should be dealt in accordance with the Constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
