<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, August 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak insisted
Wednesday that time is still not ripe for renewing Israeli-
Palestinian peace talks following the failure of last month's Camp
David summit.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference to launch Israel's new school
year, Barak said that if the Palestinians show more flexibility
and openness, the negotiations could be jump-started. However, he
added, he had not seen the signal. (Israel-Palestinian-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia will start to retrieve the bodies of the
crewmen of the nuclear submarine Kursk, which sank in the Barents
Sea during a military exercise on August 12, at the end of
September, Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov announced Wednesday.
(Russia-Submarine Crew-Salvage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Afghanistan's anti-Taliban forces Wednesday
claimed to have captured an important town in eastern Afghanistan,
reported the Afghan Islamic Press (AIP).
</P>
<P>
The Pakistan-based press agency quoted opposition sources as
saying that the opposition troops seized Darra-e-Nour, some 35
kilometers from key eastern city of Jalalabad, after fierce
fighting against the Taliban troops. (Afghan-Fighting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt on Wednesday reiterated the full implementation
of U.N. Security Council resolutions in order that East Jerusalem
be placed under Palestinian sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The question of Jerusalem is "extremely important and sensitive
" in the Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations, Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa said after a meeting between Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in
Alexandria. (Egypt-Palestine-Jerusalem)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- A court in the east German city of Halle on Wednesday
sentenced three skinheads to prison terms ranging from life to
nine years for beating a Mozambican to death, Deutsche Presse-
Argentur (DPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
A 24-year-old accused was sentenced to life imprisonment and
two 16-year-old youths were each given nine years for the murder
of Alberto Adriano on June. (Germany-Racism-Conviction)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- Two more Tutsi parties have put their
signatures to the Burundi peace and reconciliation agreement aimed
at ending the seven-year civil war in the country, bringing to six
the number of the minority Tutsi parties which have so far signed
the peace deal. (Burundi-Deal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- Australian Prime Minister John Howard said
Wednesday that his country could not support an open-ended
commitment to keep troops in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Howard told ABC television that Australia would not walk away
from its responsibilities in East Timor, but the government could
not support an open-ended commitment to keeping troops on the
ground there. (Australia-East Timor)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- The French company Aerospatiale-Matra Missiles
admitted Wednesday that it has signed a contract of missile sales
with a "secret Asian country."
</P>
<P>
The contract covers the sale of sea-to-sea missiles and others,
said the company, which is affiliated to the European Aeronautics,
Defense and Space group. (France-Missiles-Asia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said Wednesday
that France will continue the process of normalizing relations
with Libya, which has helped arrange the release of three French
hostages by the Philippine Muslim rebels.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the daily Le Figaro, Vedrine said that the
process of normalization of relations between Libya and the
European Union (EU) began one and a half years ago when the United
Nations suspended its sanctions against Libya after Tripoli agreed
to hand over the suspects in the 1988 bombing of a Pan-Am
passenger plane over Lockerbie. (France-Libya-Ties)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- Negotiators from the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) and South Korea on Wednesday agreed on two or three
more family reunions, the restoration of a rail link and the
exchange of tourist groups.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to discuss investment protection and double
taxation, media reports said. (DPRK-SKorea-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on Wednesday flew to
Colombia for a visit to show his support for the fight against
drug trafficking with an aid of 1.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
He will just stay at the scenic Caribbean port city of
Cartagena, site of a major hemispheric drug summit 10 years ago
and far from the violence for security. (Clinton-Colombia-Visit)
</P>
</TEXT>
