<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgian Government Refuses to Raise Retirement Age </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Belgian Minister of Social
Affairs and Pensions Frank van den Broucke said Wednesday that he
does not want the retirement age in the country to be raised from
65 to 68.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came as some experts proposed the rise "in order to
keep the pension system affordable."
</P>
<P>
Describing the proposal as "asocial," the minister said many
people usually do not work toward the age of 65. Moreover, he said,
it is more appropriate to improve working conditions first so that
people can continue working at an older age.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said he will negotiate an arrangement with
trade unions and employers' organizations to discourage early
retirement schemes.
</P>
<P>
Employees should be able to take more breaks out of work, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
