<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Strengthen Banking Regulation, Audit Board </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- A protocol was signed Thursday in
Turkey to transfer some authorities of the Central Bank and the
Treasury to the Banking Regulation and Audit Board (BDDK) and
adjust the cooperation principles among these three institutions.
</P>
<P>
Treasury Undersecretary Selcuk Demiralp, Central Bank Chairman
Gazi Ercel and BDDK Chairman Zekeriya Temizel signed the protocol
at the BDDK building, Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the protocol, the Treasury will transfer three
quadrillion Turkish Liras (TL) to the BDDK for the Savings Deposit
Insurance Fund.
</P>
<P>
This money is equivalent to almost 5 billion U.S. dollars and
the BDDK will re-pay this money back to the Treasury in every
three months.
</P>
<P>
Turkish officials earlier announced that almost 5-billion dollar
finance is required for the rehabilitation of eight banks
transferred to the BDDK.
</P>
<P>
Temizel said that today is the beginning of a new era for
Turkish
banking system as the BDDK, an independent institution, will be
inspecting the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
Temizel said the move also means that Turkey will fully obey the

international rules defined by Basel Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
"The new system will bring trustable inspection and monitoring
to banking sector which will be in line with international norms.
Individual and international investors will base their preferences
of banks on accurate and dependable information," he said.
</P>
<P>
Demiralp said Treasury which successfully regulated and
inspected the banking sector for many years is handing over this
responsibility to the BDDK as of Thursday, adding that his ministry
would assist the BDDK, especially in the necessary fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
But Temizel said, "His board did not aim to terrorize banks by
threatening them with fines. It aimed to make banks obey rules and
bring feasible regulations in the shortest time possible."
</P>
<P>
Stressing the importance of the protocol, Ercel said this was a
big step in the collection, evaluation and coordination of
information among the institutions.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the signing ceremony, the Central Bank Chairman said
that a healthy macro-economic environment should be formed for a
healthy banking system and an effective inspection system should
start.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
