<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Backs Peace Process on Israeli-Palestinian Track: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Visiting British Minister of State
for Foreign Affairs Peter Hain said here Thursday that his country
will support the peace process on the Palestinian-Israeli track
until a final solution is attained.
</P>
<P>
Hain made the pledge at a joint press conference with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat after their talks on the latest
developments of the Middle East peace process, and the Arab and
international efforts to push the process forward.
</P>
<P>
"We are good friends of the Palestinian people and we will
continue backing the peace process till a final and historic
solution is reached by the Palestinian and Israeli leaders," Hain
said.
</P>
<P>
The British minister added that he conveyed an invitation from
British Prime Minister Tony Blair to Arafat for a meeting to
discuss ways for pushing forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Arafat said the efforts being made by Blair were
very important for keeping the peace process on track.
</P>
<P>
Britain, an important member of the European Union (EU) and one
of the five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council, is very
interested in the peace process. And Britain is an essential force
for the peace process, Arafat noted.
</P>
<P>
Hain arrived here on Tuesday in an effort to narrow the gaps
between the Palestinian and Israeli positions on the final status
issues. He is expected to hold talks with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak later this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
