<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's national carrier Turkish Airlines (THY)
suffered losses of 170 million U.S. dollars in 1999 and 65 million
in the first half of 2000, reported Turkish Daily News on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Turkish Association of Private Aviation
Companies Safi Ergin told reporters that private airlines suffered
a loss of 102 million dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
He said that apart from the 1999 financial crisis, last year's
two devastating earthquakes, rising fuel oil prices and dollar/euro
parity also worsened the situation.
</P>
<P>
Ergin said that the government had paid for the losses of THY
and those of the private airlines should also be paid by the
government.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if the government fails to take necessary
measures for next year, foreign tour operators will choose Egypt,
Tunisia and Greece over Turkey.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) saw its imports
volume from Britain during the first half of the year rose to 4.16
billion dirhams (1.14 billion U.S.dollars), up by 10 percent from
3.77 billion dirhams (1.03 billion dollars) the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
However, UAE's exports to Britain in the first six months of the
year recorded some unevenness, the official WAM news agency
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The exports volume from Dubai fell 12 percent to 1.40 billion
dirhams (300.5 million dollars), while those from the northern
emirates were down 169.95 million dirhams (46.43 million dollars)
from 180.4 million dirhams (49.3 million dollars) the same period
of last year.
</P>
<P>
But Abu Dhabi's exports to Britain increased 22 percent to 281.6
million dirhams (76.9 million dollars) from 231 million dirhams
(63.1 million dollars) in the first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The World Bank has recently put off the release of the
first tranche of the Financial Sector Adjustment Loan (FSAL) of 390
million U.S. dollars to Turkey, reported Turkish Daily News on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
World Bank Financial Sector Desk Chief Lalit Raina told
reporters Thursday that the Turkish government had pledged that
state banks will be sold off, and the World Bank will wait until
this pledge is fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
Raina said that Turkish government is reluctant to privatize
state banks, which account for 40 percent of Turkey's banking
sector.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has pledged to give Turkey a total of 1.5 billion
dollars in FSAL.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The U.S.-based Exide Corporation recently announced
that it will build an automotive batteries manufacturing plant in
the Jebel Ali Free Zone of the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
"The new facility in Dubai will help us reach customers with the
right product at the right time," Ravinder S. Sokhi, marketing
director of the Middle East Operations, was quoted by the official
WAM news agency as saying on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The plant, at an investment of over 18 million dirhams (4.92
million U.S. dollars), has a capacity to produce 750,000 batteries
per year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides the new one in Jebel Ali, Exide has three other plants
in Saudi Arabia, one each in Muscat and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Exide has been supplying batteries to the UAE through its
authorized distributor, Al Kharbash Group of Companies. It has been
selling about 30,000 batteries a year in the UAE since it entered
the market in 1999.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Israel is stepping up preparations to purchase water
from Turkey following the visit by Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak to Turkey on August 28, reported Anatolia News Agency on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The construction of a 13-kilometer-long pipeline from the
discharging installations in Ashkelon, southern Israel, to the main
reservoir in Nohora has started. The project, which is expected to
cost 20 million U.S. dollars, is expected to be completed by mid-
2001. Meanwhile, it was reported that Turkey had agreed to cut
the price from 23 cents one cubic meter to 8-10 cents.
</P>
<P>
Israel, which has suffered severe drought, plans to purchase 45
million cubic meters of water at the first stage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
