<HEADLINE> Congolese Resistance Party Asks for Foreign Troop Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Union of Congolese
Resistance Forces (UCRF) has appealed to Uganda, Rwanda and
Burundi to withdraw their troops from the Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC) to avoid unnecessary loss of lives on all parties
involved in the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Addressing journalists here on Thursday, Mulengwa Bagiel,
chairman of the UCRF, cautioned that should the plea fall in a
deaf ear, his union would mobilize people to make assault.
</P>
<P>
"In the meantime, we invite all political parties and armed
groups to join the UCRF platform in order to canalize all efforts
towards peace," said Mulengwa.
</P>
<P>
He called on several major warring factions in the DRC, which
he said are working for foreign interests, to come to their senses
and put the interest of the people first.
</P>
<P>
Rebels backed by Rwanda, Uganda and Burundi, who have been
fighting the DRC government led by Laurent Kabila since August
1998, control large parts of the east and north of the country.
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia are supporting the Kabila government.
</P>
<P>
A cease-fire agreement was agreed in the Zambian capital,
Lusaka, in July 1999, but it has not been respected by any of the
parties and the fighting has continued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
