<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Equatorial Guinea Resolve Maritime Boundary Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and its neighboring
Equatorial Guinea have reached an agreement on the delimitation of
their long-disputed maritime boundary, the News Agency of Nigeria
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian Foreign Ministry hailed the agreement as opening a
new chapter in bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement that the agreement is to end
the 10-year-long negotiations between the two countries on a
disputed maritime boundary spanning on oil-rich waters.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is made possible with concessions by the Nigerian
side on an oil block, with 30 million barrels of estimated reserve,
according to the Nigerian statement.
</P>
<P>
It will be signed by the two presidents at a scheduled meeting
in the near future in Malabo, the capital of Equatorial Guinea.
</P>
</TEXT>
