<HEADLINE> Oil Producers, Consumers to Meet in Riyadh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Oil producers and consumers
will examine in-depth problems of the international market during
a meeting around mid November in Riyadh, OPEC President Ali
Rodriguez said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At this meeting, delegates will talk about adopting the price
band system planned by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC), Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
OPEC hopes that in line with the price band system, crude has a
minimum price of 22 U.S. dollars per barrel and a maximum of 28
dollars, for a balance between producers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
The Riyadh meeting will follow the OPEC summit programmed for
September 27 and 28 in Caracas, Rodriguez said. He is also
Venezuela's energy and mines minister.
</P>
<P>
Heads of Saudi Arabia, Iraq, Kuwait and Libya declined
attending the summit due to security or health problems.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC, which was created in 1960, is made up of Venezuela,
Saudi Arabia, Iraq, Iran, Kuwait, Libya, Algeria, United Arab
Emirates, Indonesia, Qatar and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the band system, if price maintains itself
for 20 days above or below the limit, OPEC will increase or bring
down crude extraction.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman from Venezuela's Energy and Mines
Ministry, the Caracas summit statement will be prudent and not
promote the extreme defense of OPEC interests but rather the
understanding of producers and consumers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
