<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Ruling Party Wraps Up Caucus with Calm Optimism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Canada's ruling Liberal Party is
wrapping up a three-day caucus in Winnipeg, Manitoba, with calm
optimism about its leading position for the next election and an
imminent health deal with provinces.
</P>
<P>
Party pollster Michael Marzolini gave Liberal members of
parliament Wednesday a cautiously optimistic picture to urge them
to "stay down the middle" for the victory of the next election,
which could be expected at any time between the fall 2000 and the
spring 2001.
</P>
<P>
According to Marzolini's "snapshot of the nation," the
Liberals take a lead of 43 to 23 percent against its arch-rival,
the newly formed Canadian Alliance party.
</P>
<P>
The pollster put the rates of support for the country's New
Democrats (NDP) at 12 percent, the Bloc Quebecois at 11 percent
and the Tories at nine percent.
</P>
<P>
The optimism appeared cooler than another poll released on the
same day by local media, which showed 46 percent of support for
Liberals, 22 percent for the Canadian Alliance and 10 percent for
either the Tories or the NDP.
</P>
<P>
Marzolini claimed the ruling party still enjoys a commanding
lead in public opinion, Prime Minister Jean Chretien is still the
most popular leader and, if an election were held today, the party
would win a third consecutive majority.
</P>
<P>
But he also warned that Liberals cannot take victory for
granted simply on their record. They must better respond to
Canadians' priorities including health care, the environment and
tax relief, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chretien, who reiterated his confidence to lead the
party to a new victory Tuesday night at the opening of the caucus,
expressed a virtual certainty Wednesday for a health care deal
next month to end years of squabbling between the federal and
provincial governments.
</P>
<P>
"I think we're very close," Chretien told reporters after
meeting with Manitoba Premier Gary Doer, who is spokesman for the
provinces this year.
</P>
<P>
"Ninety to 95 percent of the road has been covered. We think
that if everything works well, there will be an agreement between
the first government and the provincial governments," he said.
</P>
<P>
The deal is expected at a meeting on September 11, when
Chretien and the premiers would work toward an agreement on the
demand that Ottawa increase the Canada Health and Social Transfer
to the provinces to 18.7 billion Canadian dollars (about 12.7
billion U.S. dollars) from 15.5 billion (about 10.5 U.S. dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Russian Fleet Commander Deplores Poor Financing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 31 (Xinhua) -- A former Russian fleet commander
said Thursday all the misfortunes of the Russian Navy are due to
insufficient financing and that if the problem is not addressed
properly, tragedies like the sinking of the Kursk nuclear
submarine that killed 118 servicemen may reoccur.
</P>
<P>
Admiral Oleg Yerofeyev, who commanded the Northern Fleet from
1992-1999, said the lack of financing also reflects negatively on
prospects for the Russian Navy's development.
</P>
<P>
In an interview that appeared on the Thursday edition of the
Russikiye Vesti newspaper, Yerofeyev listed construction of the
Yury Dolgoruky new-generation strategic submarine as an example.
</P>
<P>
Because the project is going "far too slowly... a strategic
submarine equipped with expensive weapons is becoming obsolete
already on the docks," Yerofeyev said.
</P>
<P>
On what caused the Kursk to go down to the bottom of the
Barents Sea during naval exercises, Yerofeyev said he does not
believe that the sub had collided with another vessel.
</P>
<P>
A collision with another heavy object was one of the possible
reasons listed by a government commission investigating the
incident.
</P>
<P>
Yerofeyev said the region "is closed for 10 days" during
training exercises and that "the heads of all companies owning any
seagoing vehicles are informed of the training."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the reports of a possible collision with a
British submarine, he said: "I do not believe that the
administration of Great Britain and its navy are so cynical as to
blatantly lie to the entire world community. It is impossible to
hide such a fact."
</P>
<P>
"A foreign submarine would have been seriously damaged and
there would have been submariners in it," Yerofeyev said.
Therefore, it should have either entered a dock for repairs or
been written off. "Americans have written off two of their
submarines after collisions with ours," he recalled.
</P>
<P>
"In other words, a collision cannot be concealed. If it is
indeed confirmed, then the British prime minister will have to
resign at once," the Interfax news agency quoted the admiral as
saying in the interview.
</P>
<P>
In another related development, a recent poll show that 31
percent of Russians consider the Kursk sinking a tragic misfortune
while 28 percent see it as an indication of the technical
imperfection of Russian military technology.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Interfax reported the results of the poll, which
was conducted by the All-Russia Center for the Study of Public
Opinion on August 28 and involved 1,600 Russians.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll, 21 percent of the respondents consider
the tragedy an indication of the government's poor control over
the situation in the armed forces, 20 percent see it a result of
mistakes made by the Navy command. Eighteen percent think it is
due to the command's inability to ensure necessary cooperation
with ships and rescuers.
</P>
<P>
Only 13 percent of respondents believe the catastrophe was
caused by hostile actions on the part of NATO military forces,
Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Of those polled, 19 percent say the commander of the Northern
Fleet must resign over the tragedy; 21 percent believe the
commander of the Russian Navy should step down.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev and President Vladimir Putin
were also on the list. Nineteen percent of those polled say
Sergeyev should resign whereas 16 percent say Putin should stand
down.
</P>
<P>
On August 23, the national day of mourning for the 118
submariners, Putin told the Russians on national television that
he felt "fully responsible and guilty" for the tragedy, but he
refused to accept the resignations tendered by Sergeyev, Navy
Commander-in- Chief Admiral Vladimir Kuroyedov and Northern Fleet
Commander Vyacheslav Popov.
</P>
<P>
He said the causes and circumstances of the sinking of the
Kursk should first be clarified.
</P>
<P>
To accept someone's resignation or fire someone "is the easiest
and most erroneous way out" of the tragic situation, but that "
does not change the essence of the matter," Putin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Host NATO Submarine Rescue Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Turkey will host the submarine
escape and rescue (SMER) maneuver, or Sorbet Royal-2000, of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization at its southern Mersin Gulf on
September 4-13.
</P>
<P>
Anatolia News Agency reported on Thursday that Turkish Naval
Forces Commandership announced in a statement that NATO members
Turkey, Italy and the United States will despatch naval units and
rescue experts to attend the maneuver.
</P>
<P>
Sorbet Royal-2000 aims to develop cooperation and coordination
among the participating countries in underwater rescue operations,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The maneuver, which is conducted every three years, is one of
the main NATO maneuvers, will test NATO's capability to rescue crew
members from a sunken submarine.
</P>
<P>
Turkey will participate with three submarines, an attack boat, a
rescue ship, a submarine survey ship, four coast guard boats and
several helicopters and airplanes.
</P>
<P>
Sweden, Argentina, Australia, Chile, Singapore, Israel, India
and Egypt will participate as observers in the exercise.
</P>
<P>
"The rescue efforts at the Russian submarine which sank on
August 12, 2000 warrant the need for fast cooperation among
countries in submarine rescue efforts," said the statement.
</P>
