<HEADLINE> Iraqis to Be Able to Watch More TV Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqis will soon be able to
watch more television channels with more broadcast hours, a source
at the ministry of culture and information said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The source said that the ministry is negotiating with an
international company specializing in manufacturing satellite
antennas in order to upgrade Iraq's TV system within the coming six
months.
</P>
<P>
If everything goes smoothly, the TV channels that Iraqi people
can watch will be increased to seven at first, then to 14, from the
present three, which broadcast programs about 12 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
The broadcast hours will be ultimately increased to 24 hours a
day, the source said.
</P>
<P>
This surely sounds good for the Iraqi people, who suffered most
under the crippling sanctions imposed by the United Nations
following the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
But the staggering price may make them balk at tuning in for the
service which, according to the source, will cost about 320 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The average income of government employees is about 50,000 Iraqi
dinars (25 dollars) a month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
