<HEADLINE> Cyprus Cabinet Approves 2001 State Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus cabinet on Thursday
approved the 2001 state budget, which projects 2,417.0 million
Cyprus pounds (4,834.0 million U.S. dollars) in expenditure and 1,
576.0 million pounds (3,152 million dollars) in revenue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a two-hour cabinet meeting, Finance Minister
Takis Clerides expressed his satisfaction with the performance of
Cyprus economy in 2000, and predicted "encouraging prospects for
2001" with an estimated rate of growth at 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit is estimated at 841.0 million pounds (1,682.0
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Public deficit is expected to show slight improvement and be
restricted to 190.9 million pounds (381.8 million dollars) in 2001
from 210.6 million pounds (421.2 million dollars) the year before.
</P>
<P>
Inflation, he said, is expected to rise to 4.2 percent compared
with 1.7 percent in 1999, due primarily to the increase in oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
Expenditures on development projects for 2001 are expected to
reach 292.0 million pounds (584.0 million dollars) compared with
286.8 million pounds (573.6 million dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
Some 55 million pounds (110 million dollars) will go to
improving the road network, another 23 million pounds (46 million
dollars) to water projects, 7 million pounds (14 million dollars)
to infrastructure at the island's two airports and about 25 million
pounds (50 million dollars) will go to education.
</P>
<P>
The budget has no provision for the creation or upgrading of new
posts in the civil service, Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
The budget will be tabled to the House of Representatives for
approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
