<HEADLINE> Cyprus Entitled to Join European Army: DM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has both the right and the
obligation to join the European Union (EU) Common and Foreign
Security Policy, Defense Minister Socrates Hasikos said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The remark was made in response to loud criticism from the
Turkish Cypriot side in the north of the divided island about the
Cyprus government's attempt to join the European army.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the island's southern Larnaca airport before heading
for Athens for a private visit, Hasikos said Cyprus' EU accession
course is a one-way street and a strategic policy choice, adding
that "our effort to be part of the European army must be seen
within this context."
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus News Agency, Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash has threatened to leave the U.N.-sponsored proximity
talks, due to resume next month in New York, if the EU makes any
further move to bring Cyprus closer to joining the European army.
</P>
<P>
Hasikos pointed out that Cyprus is already engaged in the
process of participation in its capacity as a candidate country,
and is set to attend in November a meeting of the 15-member EU with
other candidate states, one of which is Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He said Denktash's remarks targeted the EU and not the Cyprus
Republic.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Denktash's threats would affect the talks, Hasikos
hoped this would not be the case.
</P>
<P>
"What will affect the talks is the approach Ankara and Denktash
will adopt and whether the Turkish Cypriot leader will go with a
sincere disposition and will to find a peaceful, lasting and viable
settlement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides
since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the northern third of
the island following a failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have held three rounds of U.N.-sponsored proximity
talks in an effort to find a solution in the island, but so far no
tangible results have been achieved. The fourth round of talks are
scheduled to start on September 12 in New york. 
</P>
</TEXT>
