<HEADLINE> France to Cut 120 Billion Francs of Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The French government will cut a
total of 120 billion francs (17 billion U.S. dollars) of taxes
from 2001 to 2003, including a general lowering of income tax.
</P>
<P>
French Minister of Economy, Finance and Industry Laurent Fabius
announced at a press conference that in three years from 2001, all
the rates in income tax will be cut by a total sum of 45 billion
francs (6.4 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Although people with all levels of income will benefit from the
measure, it will most benefit those with the least income,
according to the minister who announced the budget project for the
year 2001 at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Next year alone, taxes will drop by 60 billion francs (8.5
billion U.S. dollars), according to budget project.
</P>
<P>
The government has already decided to cut 80 billion francs (11.
5 billion U.S. dollars) of taxes for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Due to the rise of fuel prices, the road tax disc for
automobiles will be cancelled for individual car owners from
November but will be maintained for vehicles belonging to
companies.
</P>
<P>
Those with a minimum income guaranteed, also called SMIC, will
have their income increased by 540 francs (77 U.S. dollars) --
about 10 percent of their salary -- each month by 2003, because of
tax cutting.
</P>
<P>
Other measures will include lowering taxes on social
contributions by people of low income and the tax on consumption
of certain oil products because of their rising costs, and the
cancellation of a 10 percent extra tax on the income of companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
