<HEADLINE> Russia Airs Surprise at U.S. Position on Alleged Spy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Moscow expressed surprise
Thursday at statements made by the U.S. State Department on Russia
's s detention of an American citizen on charges of espionage.
</P>
<P>
"What is most surprising is the attempts made by U.S. officials
to assert his innocence, something that only investigating and
judicial bodies can do," the Interfax news agency quoted the
Russian Foreign Ministry as saying in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Hints made by State Department officials about a possible link
between Pope's case and the development of Russian-U.S. trade and
economic links are especially worrying," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian statement came after U.S. State Department
Spokesman Philip Reeker's remarks Tuesday that Washington was
examining the implications for U.S. business travelers of the five-
month long imprisonment of Pope, a retired U.S. Navy intelligence
officer.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Federal Security Service (FSB) accuses Pope of
having made contact with a Russian scientist, saying he was
gathering data on a Russian underwater missile.
</P>
<P>
"Russian law-enforcement agencies have evidence that Pope
collected secret data on Russia's defenses. The investigation has
been brought to completion, Pope and his attorneys are studying
the case that will be sent to court," the Russian Foreign Ministry
statement said.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. State Department said that Pope should be
released because "no evidence exists that he has violated Russian
laws.
</P>
<P>
Washington also expressed concern over the treatment of Pope,
who is reportedly in remission from bone cancer, but a Moscow
court rejected Pope's request to be released on bail after Russian
physicians' conclusion that Pope was fit enough to stand trial.
The Moscow city court would hear Pope's appeal on September 11.
</P>
<P>
"The investigation met the requirements of Russian and
international law. In particular, Pope has an attorney, members of
the U.S. embassy staff have seen him on several occasions and
meetings with his wife are being organized," the Russian statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Pope has had regular medical examinations. Russian doctors say
they think his health is satisfactory. His medical history, made
available by the Americans as late as August 23, is being studied,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The document said Washington's "attempts to put pressure on the
investigating and judicial bodies do not add to the prestige of
the United States, which has declared that law is its overriding
principle."
</P>
<P>
"What we are witnessing is a new manifestation of double
standards," the statement said. "The U.S. authorities show no
leniency to people convicted on similar charges inside the United
States, whatever the state of their health, but want other
countries to use a different approach."
</P>
<P>
"This policy is unacceptable," the statement said, noting that
Russian judiciary bodies must have the last say in the matter.
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted the FSB as saying that Pope, after his
retirement from the U.S. Navy intelligence establishment,
regularly visited Russia as a representative of the University of
Pennsylvania and later as the head of the TechSource Marine Group
Ltd. private company.
</P>
<P>
It said Pope visited research institutes in Moscow, St.
Petersburg, Novosibirsk and other Russian cities, which were
involved in creating high-speed underwater and above- water
objects.
</P>
<P>
The FSB public relations center said Pope was especially
interested in a high-speed underwater rocket adopted by the
Russian Navy. When launched from a submarine, such a rocket can
move at a speed of over 100 meters per second.
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted experts as describing the weapon as the most
effective one in a so-called "boat duel," and even light boats
equipped with such a rocket are capable of destroying a modern
warship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
