<HEADLINE> Britain Angry Over France's Domestic Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- France's domestic dispute over
rising oil prices has made Britain angry because thousands of
British tourists are stranded in France by fishermen's protests,
European Union (EU) officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Britain has made clear that it was angry at being caught up in
a domestic French dispute which prevented thousands of tourists
from returning home.
</P>
<P>
The British travelers had to try to cross the Dover Channel
these days at Ostend and Zeebrugge, the port cities of Belgium.
They are joined by hundreds of trucks queuing to get into ferries
at Zeebrugge.
</P>
<P>
In the past two days, shipping company Sea France diverted its
vessels via Ostend. P&AMP;O Stena Line, another shipping firm, added
extra ships to the Zeebrugge-Dover link.
</P>
<P>
French fishermen had blocked most of France's major ports in
protest against high oil prices. They want supportive measures
from the government. Their actions caused problems at ferry ports,
including Calais, this week.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, French fishermen agreed to end their
blockade after reaching agreement with the government. However,
British Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott is planning to meet
French ministers and the European Commission, the European Union's
executive arm, to discuss whether such a protest action was legal.
</P>
<P>
"Holding Britain to ransom because of an industrial dispute or
a dispute in France is totally unacceptable to us," Prescott said.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation EU is worried about the high oil prices
throughout its member states. A spokesman for the European
Commission told a news briefing here that the commission will
discuss the issue at its first meeting after the summer break on
September 6.
</P>
<P>
A number of EU governments, faced with growing protests, have
announced or are planning to compensate sensitive sectors, such as
transport, for the rise in prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
