<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New U.N. Weapons Team For Iraq Ready to Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The new U.N. weapons team
for Iraq said on Thursday that it is ready to begin its work in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In a written report to the United Nations Security Council,
Hans Blix, head of the United Nations Monitoring, Verification and
Inspection Commission (UNMOVIC) for Iraq, gave an account of
recent recruitment, training and organizational activities.
</P>
<P>
Blix, former head of the Vienna-based International Atomic
Energy Agency, said UNMOVIC's first training course for 44 people
representing 19 nationalities was held from July 11 to August 10,
mostly in New York.
</P>
<P>
In addition to weapons-related instruction, he said,
participants received cultural training from Columbia University
academics on such topics as the history, economy, politics and
society of Iraq as well as on regional, social and religious
themes.
</P>
<P>
Preparations are under way for the second training course,
which is planned to be held in France form November 7 to December
8, Blix said.
</P>
<P>
With the completion of the first course and the recruitment of
a sufficient number of professional and trained core staff, the
commission could plan and commence a number of activities in Iraq
which would be necessary to prepare for monitoring, verification
and inspection envisaged by the United Nations Security Council,
Blix said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. weapons inspection team has been away from Iraq since the
U.S.-led military strikes against the country in December 1998.
Iraq has reiterated that lifting the sanctions is the precondition
for the weapons team to return.
</P>
<P>
UNMOVIC was established in December 1999 to replace the United
Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraq'
s weapons of mass destruction. UNSCOM was accused by Iraq of
working for the United States.
</P>
<P>
According to the relevant resolution of the United Nations
Security Council, sanctions against Iraq cannot not be lifted
until the U.N. clarifies that Iraq has destroyed all its weapons
of mass destruction. Iraq has been under stringent U.N. sanctions
since its invasion of Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
