<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Factory Orders Fall by Record 7.5 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- New orders to U.S. factories
plunged by a record 7.5 percent in July, led by the biggest-ever
monthly drop in demand for airplanes and other transportation
equipment, the Commerce Department reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Total factory orders fell to a seasonally adjusted rate of 377.
6 billion U.S. dollars in July, down from 408.1 billion dollars in
June.
</P>
<P>
In June, factory orders rose a revised 5.2 percent. That was
slightly weaker than the government reported one month ago.
</P>
<P>
Orders for transportation equipment fell a record 31.8 percent
in July, thanks to a drop in demand for airplanes and aircraft
parts. In June, transportation orders rose a huge 41.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile transportation category, factory orders
fell a modest 2.6 percent in July. The transportation sector
swings widely from month to month because it includes costly items
such as airplanes, ships and tanks.
</P>
<P>
Orders for durable goods, big-ticket manufactured items
expected to last at least three years, fell by a record 12.4
percent after a 9.2 percent increase in June. Demand for
nondurable goods, such as food and fuel, fell 0.3 percent, after a
0.1 percent decrease in June.
</P>
<P>
Shipments, a barometer of current production, fell by 1.2
percent last month after posting a 0.8 percent increase in June.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has boosted interest rates six times over
the last 14 months to slow the economy and keep inflation under
control.
</P>
<P>
In another report, the Commerce Department said consumers spent
5.5 billion dollars shopping in cyberspace during the second
quarter of the year. That was 5.3 percent higher than the 5.2
billion dollars posted in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
E-commerce sales in the second quarter accounted for 0.68
percent of total sales, down from 0.7 percent in the January-March
quarter.
</P>
<P>
The government in March began issuing quarterly estimates of
such sales in an effort to show the impact the Internet is having
on the American economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECB Raises Interest Rates by 0.25 Percentage Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The European Central Bank (ECB)
on Thursday raised its key interest rate by 0.25 percentage points
to 4.5 percent in a bid to ease the pressure of a rising inflation
in the 11-nation single currency area.
</P>
<P>
It is imperative that medium-term upward pressure on prices be
contained, said the bank in a statement after a Governing Council
meeting.
</P>
<P>
It hoped the rate hike could "support the favorable prospects
for high economic growth in the euro area.
</P>
<P>
The ECB has warned of medium-term price instability and
possible rises in inflation in the eurozone as a result of the
euro's weakness and the high oil prices on world market.
</P>
<P>
However, there are worries that the rate rise could choke off
recovery of the German economy, which is Europe's largest.
</P>
<P>
The rise is the sixth in 10 months in the ECB benchmark minimum
bidding rate. The bank is charged with maintaining price stability
in the eurozone, which it has translated into keeping annual
inflation below 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
In July, the eurozone's average consumer price inflation
remained unchanged from June at 2.4 percent. This prompted the ECB
chief economist Otmar Issing to say that the chance to keep
eurozone's inflation within the 2 percent limit is little.
</P>
<P>
Further evidence of inflationary pressure came during the past
week with news that German producer prices are growing at their
fastest pace in nine years, chiefly due to increase in the cost of
imported energy.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the ECB's dilemma is that a rate rise could dampen
economic growth across Europe.
</P>
<P>
Despite the rate rise, the euro is at the moment still near its
record low against the U.S. dollar at the level of 0.89. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Should Rely on Itself in Economic Development: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 31 (Xinhua) -- First Vice-Premier Yuri Yekhanurov
said Wednesday that Ukraine should readjust its policies of
economic development and rely on its own efforts.
</P>
<P>
Yekhanurov pointed out that Ukraine has already been living
without external borrowings for almost one year and essentially
reduced its external and internal debts, the Interfax-Ukraine news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the International Monetary Fund's wait-and-see
attitude toward Ukraine, he said: "I believe Ukrainians should,
first of all, think how we can survive on our own efforts. I
believe we can do a good job in 2001."
</P>
<P>
The IMF suspended the funding for Ukraine on the Extended Fund
Facility (EFF) program in September 1999 due to Ukraine's failure
to meet a number of its terms.
</P>
<P>
It is reported the Ukrainian government expects the IMF Board
of Directors to resume the funding in October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
