<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Court Rejects Request of Former Turkish PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Strasbourg-based European
Court of Human Rights Thursday rejected a request from former
Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan for suspension of a one-
year prison sentence handed down to him by Turkish courts.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse quoted the defense attorney of Erbakan,
Laurent Hincker, as saying that the Second Section of the European
Court judged that the circumstances did not justify a suspension
of the sentence.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Supreme Court made definite on July 5 the
condemnation of Erbakan by the Court of Security in Diyarbakir in
southeastern Turkey, which convicted him of agitation for racial
and religious hatred and pro-Kurdish remarks during an election
campaign in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan, 74, was forced to quit premiership by the Turkish army
in 1997 which launched an anti-Islamic campaign.
</P>
<P>
His Islamist party was also dissolved in May 1998 and he was
deprived of the right to run in a legislative election in July
1998.
</P>
<P>
On July 28, Erbakan resorted to the European Court of Human
Rights, calling for a balanced new trial in his case because of
the presence of a military judge at the Court of Diyarbakir.
</P>
<P>
He also accused the Turkish authorities of depriving him of the
freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan will begin serving his prison term in 2001. According
to the Turkish criminal code, he will stay in jail for four months
and will be definitely banned from politics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
