<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Sees 20th Consecutive Quarterly Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Canada saw its 20th consecutive
quarterly growth in terms of real gross domestic product (GDP),
which increased by 1.1 percent in the second quarter of the year,
Statistics Canada reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
High-tech sectors such as computers powered the economy,
accounting for 0.5 percent increase for the quarterly growth.
</P>
<P>
Exports rose by 2.1 percent in the second quarter, while
domestic consumer spending climbed by 0.9 percent, the sixth
straight quarter of growth.
</P>
<P>
Other positive signs for the quarter were shown in revenues,
which outstripped expenditures by 30 billion Canadian dollars (
about 20.3 billion U.S. dollars) on all levels of government.
</P>
<P>
Labor income grew by 2.5 percent with the delivery of federal
equity payments.
</P>
<P>
June was also reported to be another single month of growth
with the GDP rising by 0.4 percent after a strong climb of 0.7
percent in May.
</P>
<P>
Higher manufacturing output contributed about one-third of the
0.4 percent growth in June, especially in terms of electrical and
electronic goods and auto parts.
</P>
<P>
Wholesale rose by 1.6 percent in June while retailers had gains
of 0.4 percent after flat sales in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
