<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Explore Peaceful Means for American's Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
explore peaceful means to secure the safe release of American
Jeffrey Schilling from the Abu Sayyaf group, National Security
Adviser Alexander Aguirre said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview, Aguirre noted that the government will
not appoint a special negotiator for the release of Schilling as
this is a "normal police action."
</P>
<P>
"We are not talking about the military option. We want a
successful resolution, that's why we are not thinking about that.
We are not doing anything but to conduct peaceful negotiations,"
Aguirre said.
</P>
<P>
He added that "the agencies concerned will have their own
appropriate initiatives. This is an operational matter that should
not be discussed in public, and we will see what will happen."
</P>
<P>
Aguirre said the law enforcement community is now looking into
reports from the field that Schilling may have been a willing
victim because he is a Muslim convert.
</P>
<P>
Citing reports reaching his office, Aguirre said Schilling has
no connection with the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency, as
claimed by the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf abducted Schilling On Monday and threatened to
behead him unless Washington releases Ramzi Yousef and two other
international terrorists jailed in the United States in connection
with the World Trade Center bombing several years ago.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. Embassy said in a statement that it does not deal
with terrorists, and instead demanded Schilling's unconditional
release.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Aguirre said the government is optimistic that chief
negotiator Robert Aventajado can successfully complete
negotiations for the release of the remaining hostages in Jolo.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf is still holding more than 20 Filipino and
foreign hostages in Jolo, including five hostages they abducted
from Malaysia on April 23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
