<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Liberalizes Foreign Direct Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Briefing reporters of the government decision after a cabinet
meeting, the spokesman said India would also allow oversees
venture capital funds to invest in domestic ventures subject
approval by the Security and Exchange Board of India (SEBI).
</P>
<P>
FDI upto 100 percent would be allowed in SEZs excluding
cigarettes, liquor, arms and ammunition, explosives, and allied
items of defense equipment, atomic substances, narcotics and
Psychotropic substances and hazardous chemicals.
</P>
<P>
FDI approval would also not include distillation and
manufactured tobacco substitutes, the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
In telecommunications, 100 percent FDI would be permitted
through the automatic route for internet service providers,
infrastructure providers, providing dark fiber, electronic mail
and voice mail subject to licensing and other requirements.
</P>
<P>
In respect of remaining services including basic, cellular,
long distance and other value-added services, foreign equity cap
of 49 percent would continue as at present, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Offshore venture capital funds and companies would be permitted
to invest in domestic venture capital undertakings as well as all
other companies through the automatic route subject only to SEBI
regulations.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government also cleared a proposal for payment of 2
percent royalty for exports and one percent for domestic sales
through the automatic route on use of trademarks and brand-names
of the foreign collaborator without technology transfer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0060 </DOCNO>
