<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sri Lanka's Ruling Coalition Secures Vital Support from Muslim Ally By Lian Guohui </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's ruling People's
Alliance (PA) has secured vital support from its Muslim ally in
the run-up to the 11th general elections, party sources said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka Muslim Congress (SLMC) leader and Ports Minister M.H
M. Ashraff has pledged to President Chandrika Kumaratunga that his
party will continue to support the PA at the elections due on
October 10.
</P>
<P>
Although some 35 political parties and independent groups are
expected to have joined the race for the 225-member parliament,
the main contest is between the PA and the main opposition United
National Party (UNP). The SLMC's support will surely be a shot in
the arm for the PA to win the reelection.
</P>
<P>
Ashraff, who resigned from the cabinet last week in protest
over criticism against him from a fellow Muslim minister, held
lengthy talks till early Thursday with President Kumaratunga to
agree on their electoral arrangements for the elections, party
sources said.
</P>
<P>
However, SLMC has decided that it will contest alone in four
out of the 22 electoral districts under the National Unity
Alliance (NUA). The NUA is a popular front of the SLMC formed two
years ago in a bid to give the party a national image,
transcending its eastern province based Islamic roots.
</P>
<P>
Rauf Hakeem, who was appointed on Wednesday as deputy leader
for the NUA, said the reason behind this was because the PA has
consistently lost these seats to the UNP.
</P>
<P>
Hakeem said that if the NUA were to contest alone it was
confident it would make a dent in the UNP vote bank in these areas
and be able to secure a bonus seat for the PA.
</P>
<P>
The rift between the SLMC and the PA began last week when
Transport Minister A.H.M. Fowzie issued a statement slamming the
SLMC over the party's demand for a higher quota of seats at the
elections. He said the party was a spent force which cannot get
more than five seats in the elections unless they contest with the
PA.
</P>
<P>
Ashraff resigned and went to Mecca in a huff last week although
his resignation was not accepted.
</P>
<P>
Party sources said President Kumaratunga had requested Ashraff,
who returned from Mecca on Tuesday, to continue with the PA and
assured him that there would be a disciplinary hearing against
Fowzie. Earlier, Ashraff had insisted on Fowzie's sacking even
before entering talks with the government.
</P>
<P>
However, the row has somewhat abated after the meeting with the
president until early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The SLMC, which won seven seats in the August 1994 elections,
provided crucial support which allowed Kumaratunga to form a
government even though it had only a one-seat majority.
</P>
<P>
It is rumored that the president has promised the SLMC leader
two cabinet portfolios including the post of two deputy ministers
in the event the PA is returned to power.
</P>
<P>
Hakeem said the SLMC is confident Minister Fowzie will not be
returned to cabinet in the event the PA is again voted into power.
"The president is exasperated and very bitter with him and his
constant tantrums and it is a foregone conclusion that he will not
be returned to her cabinet again," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nominations for the election opened Monday and will be kept
open by noon next Monday. Some 12 million people are eligible to
vote on October 10 to elect the next parliament under a system of
proportional representation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
