<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Fishermen Lift Blockade of Channel Tunnel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- French fishermen blocking vehicle
access to the Channel Tunnel in protest against high fuel prices
lifted the blockade at Coquelles, Pas-de-Calais, early Thursday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The lifting came after French Minister of Agriculture Jean
Glavany announced a comprehensive plan of compensation for the
fishermen, including a cut of social charges and costs for using
port facilities by the fishermen.
</P>
<P>
However, the ports of Calais and Boulogne-sur-Mer near the
Channel Tunnel remained blocked early in the afternoon, shipping
administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
Ferry services between France and England had been forced into
a standstill because of the blockade.
</P>
<P>
The fishermen have been blocking major ports across France,
including those on the North Sea, the Atlantic and the
Mediterranean, since early this week.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Eurotunnel said that owing to the blockade,
hundreds of British tourists have been prevented from returning
home. It would take three hours to clear up the traffic jam in the
area, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
