<HEADLINE> North China City to Invest 8.5 Billion Yuan in Port Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, north China's largest
port city is to allocate 8.5 billion yuan (about 102 million U.S.
dollars) in port construction in the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
According to officials with the port's administration, its
annual handling capacity is expected to exceed 100 million tons by
then.
</P>
<P>
To play an active role in west China's development and economic
globalization, the local government will improve the port's
facilities in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
The port has planned to build a 100,000-ton berth for general
goods, a 100,000-ton one for crude oil and several for containers.
It will have six 100,000-ton deep-water berths next year.
</P>
<P>
The port built a 35,000-ton berth for non-metal ores last year
and a 50,000-ton one for coke transport this year. 
</P>
