<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Five Chinese cities, namely
Taiyuan, Chongqing, Guiyang, Lanzhou and Xining, reported slight
air pollution today, with the highest pollution reading at 127 in
both Guiyang and Lanzhou.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily air quality report released by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center, level two, or fairly good air
quality, was recorded in 25 other cities.
</P>
<P>
These cities are Beijing, Tianjin, Shijiazhuang, Hohhot,
Shenyang, Changchun, Harbin, Nanjing, Wenzhou, Fuzhou, Nanchang,
Jinan, Qingdao, Yantai, Zhengzhou, Wuhan, Changsha, Shenzhen,
Zhanjiang, Nanning, Chengdu, Kunming, Xi'an, Yinchuan and Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
Particulates less than 10 microns in size were the major
pollutants in most of these cities, except Chongqing, Guiyang and
Kunming where sulfur dioxide was the major air pollutant.
</P>
<P>
Twelve cities -- Dalian, Shanghai, Suzhou, Nantong, Hangzhou,
Hefei, Xiamen, Guangzhou, Zhuhai, Shantou, Haikou, and Lhasa --
reported excellent air.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level one or excellent (pollution reading: not
exceeding 50), level two or fairly good (pollution reading: 51 to
100), level three or slightly polluted (pollution reading: 101 to
200), level four or poor (pollution reading: 201 to 300), and
level five or hazardous (pollution reading: over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored by the center include the four
municipalities of Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing,
provincial capitals and major cities in the economically developed
coastal areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Official Highlights HK's Springboard Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong official Cheung Man-
yee urged Japanese companies to pay attention to Hong Kong's
springboard role in helping international companies to establish a
foothold in the Chinese mainland, according to a report by the
Hong Kong Government Information Services Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Already the Chinese mainland's trade with Hong Kong represents
about 40 percent of our total external trade. We handle some 40
percent of China's re-exports," said Cheung, Hong Kong's principal
economic and trade representative in Tokyo, during her four-day
visit to Japan's Kyushu region, which ended Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong companies employ some five million people in wholly
or partly owned ventures in neighboring Guangdong Province and
there are more than 1,800 mainland companies operating in Hong
Kong," she said.
</P>
<P>
She told the Japanese business circle that with China's entry
to the World Trade Organization, there are forecasts that within
six years China's foreign trade and foreign investment would
double and its GDP is estimated to be 13 percent higher by 2010.
</P>
<P>
"These figures point to enormous opportunities for Hong Kong
and the entire trading world," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
