<HEADLINE> Zambia University Closed Due to Campus Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The biggest university in Zambia,
the University of Zambia ,Thursday saw an unusually large number
of buses, jeeps, pickups and cars flocking to and rushing out of
the campus, which were busy taking students home.
</P>
<P>
The students have been ordered to leave the university before
13 hours (local time) of Thursday or face arrest.
</P>
<P>
Temporary closure was announced Wednesday night after the
students turned their protest against full payment of tuition and
accommodation fees into violence on Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Zambia National Broadcasting Corporation (ZNBC)
reported Wednesday evening that Zambian police had arrested over
30 students on charge of inciting violence.
</P>
<P>
But government newspaper Times of Zambia reported Thursday that
more than 300 students were arrested on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Students went on an orgy of destruction, blocking traffic and
pedestrians from entering the campus and throwing stones at
passers-by and police, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
ZNBC quoted a police officer as saying that four vehicles were
damaged in the violence.
</P>
<P>
Another government newspaper Zambia Daily Mail reported
Thursday that 30 students were injured as police beat them up with
shot batons. Police also fired teargas to disperse the angry
students.
</P>
<P>
The management of the university demands that the students pay
130,000 Kwacha(about 40 U.S. dollars) for accommodation while
tuition fee ranges from two million Kwacha to 2.5 million Kwacha (
about 600 dollars to 760 dollars) per academic year.
</P>
<P>
The country's per capita GDP is about 400 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Registrar of the university, Susan Kapena who announced the
closure of the university, said that "the students have caused
damage to public and private property and injury to innocent
members of the public in order to coerce the administration into
changing the conditions for admission in their favor.The
university administration strongly disapprove the unruly conduct
of those students who have been misled into acts of lawlessness."
</P>
</TEXT>
