<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paris Subway Derailment Most likely Caused by Speeding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Wednesday derailment of a
subway train in Paris was most likely caused by excessive speed,
investigators said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"No definite conclusion can evidently be drawn at this stage
but the hypothesis of an excessive speed at the moment of the
derailment appears the most likely," Agence France-Presse quoted
sources close to investigation as saying.
</P>
<P>
The investigators spent the whole night at the scene of the
accident in the subway station of Notre-Dame de Lorette in
northern Paris.
</P>
<P>
They had interviewed about 30 witnesses as well as the driver
of the train, who was injured in the ear and is being treated in
hospital.
</P>
<P>
Police first suspected that something was placed on the track.
President of the Paris public transport management RATP, Jean-
Claude Bailly, said three hypotheses are the most likely --
problem with the track, mechanical failure, and fault by the
driver.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four people were injured in the accident, but none
seriously.
</P>
<P>
The first wagon of the train derailed as it was approaching the
platform of the subway station. It then overturned onto the track
of the opposition direction, stopping just one meter from another
train waiting for passengers on the platform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
