<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brian Grant Traded to Detroit Heat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Portland power forward
Brian Grant, who turned down about 200 million US dollars in deals
during this summer's NBA free-agent frenzy in an attempt to
control his own destiny, landed Wednesday in Miami.
</P>
<P>
The Heat, Cleveland and Trail Blazers pulled the trigger on a
five-player deal. Miami gets Grant, Portland gets Shawn Kemp, and
Cleveland gets Chris Gatling, Clarence Weatherspoon and a
conditional first-round pick from the Heat and Gary Grant from the
Blazers.
</P>
<P>
"There were bigger deals out there," said Brian Grant, who
signed a seven-year 86 million dollars contract in a sign-and-
trade deal, "But I didn't want to go from a first-class
organization that was a contender to an organization three or four
years away from being a contende. That's why I put myself out on a
limb to wait on a deal like Miami."
</P>
<P>
Grant who earlier was willing to take the 2.25 million salary-
cap exception to play in Miami, walked away from 40 million
dollars to become a free agent, fixed a 93 million deal with
Cleveland and turned down a 70 million offer to return to Portland.
</P>
<P>
"I did want to go back to Portland," said Grant, 28, who has
career averages of 11.8 points and 7.5 rebounds, "But as the
summer went along and I got more information, I felt I would be
used as a trading piece to acquire another big name."
</P>
<P>
His signing makes the Heat the NBA's big free-agent winner.
They've signed three new starters of Grant, Eddie Jones and
Anthony Mason from Charlotte to play alongside Alonzo Mourning and
Tim Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
Kemp, 30, has four years and 72 million dollars left on his
contract. The six-time All-star, criticized for being
overweighted and for his work ethic, will back up power forward
Rasheed Wallace and center Arvydas Sabonis.
</P>
<P>
The Cavaliers are making salary cap room. Weatherspoon and
Gatling are entering the last year of their deals. Gary Grant who
got a guaranteed 1.4 million dollars as part of the sign-and-trade
deal, likely will be cut.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
