<HEADLINE> French Diagana Struggling to Be Fit for Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Stephane Diagana, French former
400 meters hurdles world champion, is struggling to recover full
fitness for the Sydney Olympic Games, which start September 15 to
October 1.
</P>
<P>
Diagana, world champion in 1997 and the European record holder
(47.37 seconds), told Thursday's edition of sports daily L'Equipe
that he is still troubled by tendinitis in his right knee but
hopes to shake it off during pre-Games training in Perth, Western
Australia.
</P>
<P>
"It is getting better slowly," Diagana said. "The last few
days, though, I haven't trained a lot but I've been undergoing
physical therapy."
</P>
<P>
Diagana has only run one race this season and is anxious to
avoid missing a second straight Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old finished fourth in the 1992 Barcelona Games
but missed Atlanta with a stress fracture in a foot.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
