<HEADLINE> Lebanese Youth Wounded by Israeli Gunfire at Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Israeli soldiers shot and wounded
a Lebanese youth at the border flashpoint of Fatma Gate Thursday
afternoon, security source said.
</P>
<P>
Aly Fakhreddine, 20, was shot in the foot after hurling stones
at an Israeli army outpost across the barbed wire fence separating
Israel and Lebanon. He has been sent to near hospital.
</P>
<P>
The defunct border crossing of Fatma Gate become a trouble spot
since Israel ended its 22-year occupation of south Lebanon in May
and pulled its troops back behind the frontier.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people flock to the old crossing every day. Some
hurl rocks or bottles and shout insults at the Israeli soldiers,
who occasionally fire back. Several civilians have been wounded.
</P>
<P>
In Israel, the army issued a statement saying that after a
warning, soldiers had shot at the legs of civilians, wounding two
people. The army "stressed it will react to every attempt to attack
the routine and well-being of northern Israeli residents," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Israel has complained to the United Nations about the stone-
throwing incidents. The world body, which has troops stationed at
various positions along the border but not at Fatma Gate, has asked
the Lebanese authorities to seal off the area.
</P>
<P>
Fatma Gate is still controlled by the Hezbollah, or Party of
God, which spearheaded the guerrilla war against Israeli
occupation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
