<HEADLINE> U.S. Diplomat Labels Washington's Warning as Unwise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Ambassador to Beirut
John Kelly said that his country's warning to Americans of the
risks traveling to and in Lebanon was both "ill-timed and unwise,"
An Nahar newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"I feel quite safe in Lebanon," Kelly told reporters after a
visit to President Emile Lahoud at the presidential palace
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"I have noticed, since my visit last year, a positive change in
Lebanon's status abroad. There was the Israeli withdrawal from the
south followed by the visits of foreign dignitaries such as
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah
(Ibn Abdul-Aziz)," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that it is quite clear that Lebanon has regained its
former regional and international prominence after the difficult
years of the civil war that ended in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Asked about his country's warning, he replied that "I was
surprised to hear about it when I arrived at Beirut Airport".
</P>
<P>
He also described the first round of general elections as "fair
and square and the Lebanese can be proud of them".
</P>
<P>
Kelly, who is also a former assistant Secretary of State, was
Ambassador to Lebanon from August 1986 to September 1988.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department warned Americans on Monday of risks
while traveling to and in Lebanon and urged U.S. citizens in Beirut
to take special security precautions. The department said in a
statement that in case of such hazards U.S. officials may be unable
to help, saying that the situation is still unstable in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Salim Hoss Tuesday
rejected the saying and asked U.S. government to withdraw the
warning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
