<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Resolves to Strengthen Control of Small Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Senior officials from the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) have ended a three-day
workshop on the control of small arms in the sub-region, pledging
to curb the menace caused by an estimated eight million of these
arms available in the west African states, local media reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Secretary of ECOWAS Lansana Kouyate was quoted as
saying on Wednesday in Nigerian capital Abuja that security forces
of the 16-member organization have the responsibility of
monitoring the flow of arms within and outside national borders
with a view to ensuring legitimate utilization of these arms.
</P>
<P>
Kouyate said the curriculum, adopted by the workshop for the
training of security personnel on the control of small arms, would
cover general information on the diffusion of small arms, modern
techniques for the maintenance of law and order and methods of
collecting these arms and dealing with drug traffickers in the sub-
region.
</P>
<P>
The curriculum would also deal with cross border crime,
effective ways of maintaining national weapons arsenals and the
development of an information network and strategy for controlling
the menace, said Kouyate.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the workshop was a priority element of
the sub-region's plan of action for the implementation of the
ECOWAS moratorium on light weapons.
</P>
<P>
The moratorium was declared by the regional leaders for an
initial period of three years in 1998 and later followed with a
plan of action by the foreign affairs ministers at their meeting
in Bamako, capital of Mali last March and approved by the 22nd
ECOWAS summit in Lome, capital of Togo last December.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the military, police, customs and
gendarmerie of the ECOWAS member states attended the workshop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belarus Finds Objects Belonging to Viking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Belarussian archeologists have
discovered objects belonging to a Viking trader dating back to the
10th century in the flood-lands of the Berezina River in Borisovo
region, the Interfax news agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The finding includes a set of weights for weighing silver, 183
intact coins and 77 fragments of high-quality silver coins, a
silver bracelet and a sword with a silver-encrusted hilt, Interfax
said, citing senior researcher Oleg Iov.
</P>
<P>
Iov works at the Medieval Archeology Department of the History
Institute of the Belarussian Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The articles were not buried, but "were most likely lost" by a
Viking, Iov said.
</P>
<P>
Belarussian archeologists are inclined to believe that the
items sank as a result of the death of a medieval trader, who
could have fallen victim to an attack or gone overboard when he
was returning from a successful trade, Iov said.
</P>
<P>
The objects make it possible to determine the Viking's social
status, Iov said. In the Middle Ages, silver coins, weights for
weighing silver and a sword were a standard set belonging to a
trader, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Viking's things confirm the scientific hypothesis that the
way from the Varangians (Russian Vikings) to the Greeks lay not
only along the Dnieper, but along all Belarussian rivers," Iov
said.
</P>
<P>
Dnieper is a river rising in west-central Russia near Smolensk
and flowing about 2,285 kilometers southward through Belarus and
Ukraine to the Black Sea. It has been a major commercial waterway
since the ninth century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon Prapiroon Causes Damage in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Typhoon Prapiroon swept through
southern and western parts of South Korea on Thursday, destroying
numerous trees, houses and crops, said South Korea's
Meteorological Administration.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, no casualties have been reported.
</P>
<P>
The administration has issued typhoon warnings in Seoul and the
western coastal provinces of Cholla, Chungchong and Cheju Island
along with western and southwestern seas.
</P>
<P>
Prapiroon is moving northeast at a maximum speed of 25 meters
per second in the center, affecting an area of 370 kilometers in
diameter.
</P>
<P>
The typhoon is accompanied by storm, thunder and lightning,
resulting in more than 150mm of rain at the maximum nationwide.
</P>
<P>
In Cheju Island, many trees along the streets were uprooted,
some 100 houses destroyed and vehicles blown away. Electricity
poles also fell down in the typhoon, resulting in the blackout of
some 5,000 homes in Wando of South Cholla Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
