<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forerunners of Developing Western China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 31 (XINHUA) -- Wang Chuande, 73, still loves
talking about ploughing his farmland and growing crops at his home
in Hotan, northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region,
where he and more than 1,800 People's Liberation Army (PLA)
soldiers settled down to develop the Taklimakan, the biggest
desert in China, over five decades ago.
</P>
<P>
What makes him feel more happier is that he and 40 of his
former comrades-in-arms have moved into new houses which Wang
found out to be the best in the region.
</P>
<P>
Local government and the No. 47 farm where they used to work
invested one million yuan (about 120,000 U.S. dollars) to build
the new houses for them.
</P>
<P>
A group of more than 1,800 PLA soldiers traversed the
Taklimakan Desert on foot and settled down at Hotan County in
December 1949. They put down their guns and took up hoes to turn
some 666 hectares of desert into fertile farmland.
</P>
<P>
Many of the farms built by them have become major grain and
cotton production bases of China.
</P>
<P>
Even now, Wang and his former comrades-in-arms love to grow
vegetables in their courtyards, and they often recall the days
when they first set foot on the barren land in most western part
of China.
</P>
<P>
They usually say only those who have trekked through the
Taklimakan Desert can understand the saying "A journey of no
return". They are described as the first group of heroes who have
passed through the "sea of death" on foot.
</P>
<P>
They are more concerned about what happens at the No. 47 farm
today, and they watch TV programs to learn more new things.
</P>
<P>
These forerunners in developing western China have a doctor who
takes care of their health day and night. Shu Wanfu is assigned to
buy rice, flour and liquefied gas for the elderly people and take
them to scenic spots.
</P>
<P>
Liu Wenyi, 68, plans to visit Beijing some day. "I want to see
Tian'anmen Square, and to see Chairman Mao," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Today, most of the people who are working there are the
children of these veteran developers of western China.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Dayong is one of them. Zhao is now the head of the No. 47
farm which employs more than 4,000 workers. "Our fathers have
turned desert into fertile farmland, we will make it much better,"
Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
Zhao's father Zhao Chengzhang, 82, loves to hear his son
talking about the on-going development of western China. He
expects the western China will become much better in future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon Prapiroon Brushes Past Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thousands of people were evacuated from low-lying areas
overnight and many urban districts and rural counties have been
hit by strong winds and heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
The typhoon, the most severe this year, came as close as 100 km
to the city of 13 million last night, an official said.
Floodwaters had breached sections on two dyke sections in Baoshan
District and Chongming County.
</P>
<P>
Rainfall levels in Huangpu District and Chongming County
reached 85 mm and 79 mm respectively, and the rainstorm also
caused power cuts in some areas, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Troops spent around three hours piling up sandbags to repair a
breach in a dyke in the northern district of Baoshan, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the city's island county of Chongming, more than 1,200
people were evacuated as floods broke through a dyke.
</P>
<P>
But there were no reports of casualties or damage, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
