<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lions Club to Hold "World Sight Day" in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Lions Club International (
LCI) announced here today it plans to hold its 2000 "World Sight
Day" on October 12 in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Tam Wing Kun, a board appointee of the Lions Club International
and chairman of "SightFirst China Action", made the announcement
at a ceremony to see off a medical team to treat cataract patients
in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The "World Sight Day" programs include check-ups on local
schoolchildren in eight urban districts of the national capital
and a mid-term evaluation meeting on the implementation of "
SightFirst China Action" to be held at the Great Hall of the
People in downtown Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"SightFirst China Action" is part of the LCI's worldwide
program of "SightFirst" and a total of 146 million US dollars has
been raised for the program, according to Tam.
</P>
<P>
The other two co-sponsors of "SightFirst China Action" are the
China Disabled Persons Federation (CDPF) and the Ministry of
Health.
</P>
<P>
Under the five-year Chinese program, which was initiated in
1997, 1.5 million cataract Chinese will recover their sight
through operations free of charge.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that China has nine million blind people,
of them four million have lost their sight for cataracts.
Meanwhile, there are 400,000 new cataract patients in China every
year. Tam said he hopes the program will help 500,000 Chinese
cataract patients regain their sight a year.
</P>
<P>
So far, 1.2 million Chinese blind people have regained their
sight thanks to the program.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong compatriots including many aged people have donated a
lot of money, according to Tam.
</P>
<P>
Deng Pufang, chairman of the CDPF, spoke highly of the
charitable activities by the LCI and domestic and overseas people.
</P>
<P>
LCI, which was founded in 1917, is the largest international
charity group with over 43,000 sub-clubs and 1.5 million members
in over 180 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
In addition to "SightFirst China Action", the international
organization has also been involved in the building of hundreds of
"Project Hope" elementary schools and a profession training school
for the disabled in Tianjin Municipality in north China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
