<HEADLINE> Shanghai A-Share Market Hits One-Month Trough Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Composite Index
closed sharply down by 54.94 points, or 2.65 percent to finish at
2,021.20 points on Thursday, barely holding above the 30-day
moving average, after the benchmark opened 13.31 points lower in
the morning.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 14.38 billion yuan (1.73 billion US dollars),
which was 1.77 percent more than Wednesday's total, according to
Homeway, China's leading on-line financial and securities advisory
company.
</P>
<P>
The market posted its second largest tumble since the meltdown
on August 22, nose-dived to a one-month trough for an extreme lack
of investor confidence, hurt by gloomy corporate profit outlook.
One in ten Chinese listed companies reported losses for the first
six months ended June 2000.
</P>
<P>
Changchun department Store Co. Ltd. was the top gainer, adding
5.11 percent to 12.35 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou Changzhen Electrical Apparatus Co. Ltd., the biggest
loser, slid 7.71 percent to 14.60 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Homeway analysts note that the market is embroidered in rather
chopping trading as investors again turn their eyes on
fundamentals. The underlying tone is pretty vulnerable and will
trigger another round of selling pressure as sessions progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
