<HEADLINE> British Travelers Try to Return Home Through Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of British travelers
left stranded in France by French fishermen's protests are still
trying to cross the Dover Channel Thursday at Ostend and Zeebrugge,
port cities of Belgium.
</P>
<P>
They are joined by hundreds of trucks queuing to get into
ferries at Zeebrugge. At the same time, Sea France shipping
company has diverted its vessels via Ostend. P&AMP;O Stena Line,
another shipping firm, is adding extra ships to the Zeebrugge-
Dover link.
</P>
<P>
French fishermen are blockading most of France's major ports in
protest against high oil prices. They want supportive measures
from the government. Their actions caused problems at ferry ports,
including Calais, this week. According to the BBC, truck drivers
and farmers are also threatening to take similar actions.
</P>
<P>
In Belgium, the prices of diesel and household fuel are rising
sharply again, for the fifth time in two weeks. This is attributed
to limited supplies, the expensive dollar and speculations on oil
markets.
</P>
<P>
Now the European Union is worried about the high oil prices
throughout its member states. Saudi Arabia has said it is prepared
to pump up more oil to curb the prices on the international
markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
