<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Still Concerned Over High Oil Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU), still
worried about the high oil prices on the international markets,
has made its fear clear to the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC), EU sources said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
EU Energy Commissioner Loyola de Palacio expressed the EU's
concern in a telephone conversation with the current crude oil
price levels to Venezuelan President Ali Rodriguez, who is current
president of OPEC.
</P>
<P>
She told Rodriguez that the EU "would expect OPEC and the
Venezuelan presidency to contribute to a certain moderation" in
oil prices.
</P>
<P>
North Sea oil benchmark Brent price has reached a new record of
31 U.S. dollars per barrel, way above the 25-dollar per barrel
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
The EU Commissioner would like to see the price come down below
28 dollars per barrel. She also said that current price levels
penalize both producers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
So far, OPEC has not given any official reaction to EU comments,
EU sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
