to hold above the 70-point mark in the wake of Wednesday's brief
correction.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 35.76 million U.S. dollars, an increase of 101.46
percent from Wednesday's total.
</P>
<P>
According to Homeway, China's leading on-line financial and
securities advisory company, the market spent the whole session in
negative territory and gradually deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
With earnings season for the six months ended June 2000 due out
today, investors did not have much to rely on as sort of momentum
because one out of every ten Chinese companies had reported half-
year losses.
</P>
<P>
Only one issue rose, while 53 fell, with three unchanged.
</P>
<P>
China 1st Pencil lost 1.45 percent to 0.280 U.S. dollars.
Dajiang Group lost 9.93 percent to 0.272 U.S. dollars, while
Phoenix fell 9.88 percent to 0.310 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Homeway analysts note that the market can barely hang on to
positive territory with general weakness in broad areas. It has
been the usual concern about bad performing fundamentals that are
dragging B shares lower. 
</P>
