<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Build National Reclamation Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- China plans to build a national
reclamation museum to exhibit the history of cultivation on the
western frontier.
</P>
<P>
The museum is based on an existing local reclamation museum in
Shihezi City, Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
A total of 50 million yuan (about 6.1 million U.S. dollars)
will be poured into the museum which will start next year, said
Liu Ning, curator of the Shihezi Reclamation Museum.
</P>
<P>
The museum will be open to the public in two years, he said.
</P>
<P>
The People's Liberation Army (PLA) started to reclaim wasteland
in Xinjiang in 1949.
</P>
<P>
Up till now, the Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps
have 150 farms, with a population of 2.2 million. And Shihezi,
covering an area of 7,500 sq. km, with a population of 570,000,
has become an important base of the corps.
</P>
<P>
Among the 1,000-odd exhibits of Shihezi Reclamation Museum, 29
are revolutionary relics under the state's top-level preservation.
</P>
<P>
"The planned reclamation museum will have an area of 15,000
square meters, with a 7,000-square meters exhibition hall," said
Liu.
</P>
<P>
The museum will also recruit valuable cultural relics from
other production and construction corps throughout the country, in
order to show an all-round history of the reclamation of Chinese
frontiers, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu, the museum will help provide systematic
materials to study China's western regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
