<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Govt Pushes for Long-Term Thai-Cambodian Cooperation Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Cambodia have
agreed to strengthen long-term bilateral cooperation through an
economic cooperation action plan, the Thai News Agency (TNA)
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has employed the Research and Development
Institute of Kasetsart University and a group of foreign experts
to conduct a comprehensive study to be used for the drafting of
the planned long-term Thai-Cambodian Economic Cooperation Action
Plan, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The Council of the Economic Ministers approved a 20 million
baht (500,000 U.S. dollars) budget for the purpose at its meeting
this week, it stated.
</P>
<P>
The move coincides with the occasion of the 50th anniversary of
diplomatic relations between the two neighboring countries this
year.
</P>
<P>
The idea to draft the 10-year Thai-Cambodian Economic
Cooperation Action Plan was an initiative of the Office of the
National Economic and Social Development Board and related
agencies, aiming to seek a systematic framework for the
development of Thai-Cambodian relations in the fields of trade,
investment, industry and tourism in the long run, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
The move has been endorsed by the Council for the Development
of Cambodia and the Cambodian Commerce Ministry, which have also
invited Thai delegates to discuss the issue officially, it said.
</P>
<P>
The action plan is expected to provide a sector-by-sector
strategic and operational guideline crucial to the development of
economic cooperation between the two countries in short, medium
and long terms, it added.
</P>
<P>
The study of the drafting of the plan was scheduled to be
completed by next year and the cooperation guided by the action
plan, to be completed over the next years, would be implemented
through the Joint Commission on the Thai-Cambodian Cooperation, it
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
