<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Publishes First Atlas on Population, Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- China published today its first
atlas on the country's population and environment in both Chinese
and English.
</P>
<P>
Containing 184 maps, over 200 photos and graphs, and 180,000
word descriptions, the atlas offers a large collection of data and
provides analyses of scientific research on the geographic
distribution of China's 1.2 billion population, and the situation
of their health and housing as well as consumption patterns.
</P>
<P>
Published by the Science Press, the atlas also contains
information on land, water, energy, forest, grassland and
biodiversity resources and situation of the country's environment,
including land degradation and water, air and noise pollution.
</P>
<P>
Xie Zhenhua, director of the State Environmental Protection
Administration (SEPA), said today the atlas may provide useful
information for policy-makers, materials for scientific studies,
and background information for publicity campaigns aimed at
raising awareness about the need for sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
The atlas was compiled by experts from the SEPA, the Geographic
Institute of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, the China Population
and Environment Society and China Environment Monitoring Center,
with the support of the State Statistical Bureau, the State Family
Planning Commission, the Ministry of Health and the Ministry of
Land and Resources.
</P>
<P>
In the foreword of the atlas, Endymion Wilkinson, head of the
Delegation of the European Commission in China, said the EC views
the publication as an important reference document, and such a
tool should be of great help to the ever growing number of
researchers, macro-economists or environmentalists in China and
elsewhere, as well as to international institutions and the
general public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
