<HEADLINE> New Zealand, Australian Trade Ministers Discuss Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Minister for
Trade Negotiations Jim Sutton and Australian Minister for Trade
Mark Vaile met on Wednesday and Thursday in Auckland, the biggest
city of New Zealand, discussing economic relationship between the
two countries and their relations with other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
At the conclusion of their meeting, the two ministers issued a
joint statement, saying, "We had stimulating and fruitful
discussions on how we might take a fresh look at the economic
relationship between our two countries, in order to continue to
reap the gains that have been made over the last 17 years, since
the Australian-New Zealand Closer Economic Relations Agreement (
CER) was signed in 1983."
</P>
<P>
Trade ministers of the two countries have met annually to
review the implementation of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement, which was circulated here Thursday, said
the two ministers agreed that "current discussions on freer trade
between ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) and CER were a priority for
us both.
</P>
<P>
"We renewed our commitments to engage with ASEAN countries with
the objective of securing agreement to commence negotiations on a
free trade area of mutual benefit for all parties.
</P>
<P>
"We looked forward to continuing to make progress in APEC this
year under the leadership of Brunei."
</P>
<P>
On the World Trade Organization (WTO), the joint statement said
the two ministers reaffirmed their desire to "see a new round
launched at the earliest opportunity" and renewed their commitment
"to work towards this end."
</P>
<P>
On bilateral economic relationship, the joint statement said
the two countries "had a good preliminary look at ways of
deepening and enhancing our CER cooperation."
</P>
<P>
"We had a stimulating exchange of views on taking forward our
existing trans-Tasman cooperation, noted ways in which our
cooperation might be strengthened and looked ahead at how we might
build on our joint efforts to further integrate our two economies
and their potential to enhance efforts to improve the regional and
multilateral trading environment," the joint statement said.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the two ministers reaffirmed their
governments' intention to negotiate an open skies agreement
between the two countries and noted that negotiations are
scheduled to be held shortly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
