<HEADLINE> Australians Get too Lazy to Exercise: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Most Australians have got too
lazy to do enough exercise to stay healthy, according to a report
issued here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report, published by the Australian Institute of Health and
Welfare, showed that 88 percent of Australians aged between 18 and
75 believed they could be healthier by being more active.
</P>
<P>
The study found that the time spent by Australians in vigorous
activity had dropped from an average of 91 minutes per person each
week in 1997 to 65 minutes in 1999 and the proportion of
physically inactive people increased from 13 percent to 15 percent
in the same period.
</P>
<P>
Physical inactivity ranks second only to tobacco smoking as a
health risk factor in the country.
</P>
<P>
Roughly half of the population in the country are obese in
varying degrees and one in four is suffering or threatened from
diabetes or heart disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
