<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Elections Commission to Talk With Party Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Elections Commission
will hold several rounds of talks with political party leaders on
ways and manners to conduct a free and fair general election on
October 10, a senior official of the election secretariat said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed official said Commissioner of Elections Dayananda
Dissanayake will discuss with political parties the possibility of
inviting foreign observers to monitor the upcoming 11th
parliamentary elections and a final decision regarding this matter
will be taken soon.
</P>
<P>
Earlier a local media report said two election monitoring
bodies are seeking an undetermined number of international
observers and up to 10,000 local volunteers to monitor the
elections.
</P>
<P>
The Movement for Free and Fair Elections and People's Alliance
for Free and Fair Elections were involved in the election
monitoring process during last December's presidential elections
which President Chandrika Kumaratunga won for another six-year
term of office.
</P>
<P>
The official said Dissanayake had already issued instructions
to law enforcement authorities requiring them to prevent unruly
incidents and impersonation as well as to maintain law and order
during the elections.
</P>
<P>
Dissanayake briefed senior polling officers in a meeting on the
procedures to be adopted to prevent vote riggings and other poll
malpractice.
</P>
<P>
The election secretariat has also made arrangements to engage
presiding officers and other election officers in polling booths
to be set up in their residential areas for their convenience.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's 45 recognized political parties and several
independent groups have indicated that they will contest the
general elections. There are altogether 22 electoral districts
islandwide.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that more than 20 political parties have already
confirmed their desire to contest the elections but the number of
independent groups is yet to be revealed.
</P>
<P>
Almost all the parties contesting the elections are currently
in the process of finalizing their nomination lists which have to
be handed in before September 4.
</P>
<P>
Some 12 million voters are to cast their ballots at more than
10,000 polling booths to choose 225 members to the next parliament.
</P>
