<HEADLINE> HIV/AIDS Still Uganda's Big Problem: Scientist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- A French scientist has said that
in spite of the highly praised success story about Uganda's
campaign to combat the spread of HIV/AIDS, more effort is still
needed.
</P>
<P>
Luc Montagnier was quoted by Thursday's New Vision daily as
saying that "Uganda has done a lot and the infection rate has gone
down, but this is not enough."
</P>
<P>
Montagnier, who discovered the Human Immuno-deficiency Virus
causing AIDS, said he is prepared to work with Ugandan scientists
in helping them understand the mysteries of the disease.
</P>
<P>
While scientists have learnt a lot about the disease, a lot
more still remains "mysterious", like why the infection rate is
higher in sub-Saharan Africa, why treatment cannot reduce the
infection rate and how to find out alternative treatment to those
already infected, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Director of Health in Uganda's Ministry of Health
Francis Omaswa, "Uganda has reached a very critical stage in its
efforts to combat AIDS."
</P>
<P>
"We have been able to raise awareness and have had a reasonable
level of success, but there are more challenges," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
