<HEADLINE> Soaring Profits for Listed Oil Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, August 31 (Xinhua) -- China's largest overseas listed
oil company, PetroChina Company Ltd., announced today that it made
a net profit of 23.07 billion yuan in the first half of this year,
an increase of 106 per cent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The company attributed the increase in profitability to price
rises in crude oil and refined oil products and decreases in
financial expenses.
</P>
<P>
According to the company's interim results report, PetroChina
produced a total of 384 million barrels of crude oil and 241.2
billion cubic feet of natural gas in the first half of this year.
The company also processed 270 million barrels of crude oil, of
which 95 per cent is produced by the company's exploration and
production segment. The company produced 20.66 million tons of
gasoline, diesel and jet fuel.
</P>
<P>
 The Board of PetroChina has decided to pay an interim
dividend of 0.059 yuan per share to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
In the future, the company aims to continue to focus on
enhancing efficiency and cutting costs through on-going
restructuring and rationalization of its operations. To achieve
this, the company plans to shift its focus from increasing crude
oil production to maximizing return on capital. It will also shut
down inefficient refining facilities while striving to optimize
product mix for bigger market shares.
</P>
<P>
PetroChina conducted its initial public offering in both New
York and Hong Kong in April this year and issued 10 per cent of
its total equity shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Judiciary Orders Investigation Into Khoramabad Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Iran's judiciary chief Ayatollah
Hashemi Shahroudi has ordered the investigation into the riots in
the western city of Khoramabad, which have left one policeman dead
and many others injured.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Inspectorate General Hojjatoleslam Ebrahim Raisi
will head a delegation to probe the unrest and reveal the "behind-
the-scenes factors" in the violent incident, said a decree of the
judiciary chief, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The results of the investigation should be provided as soon as
possible to a judge to unveil the scandals of the rioters seeking
to strike a blow to the national security, the decree added.
</P>
<P>
The unrest broke out in Khoramabad, capital of Lorestan
province, on Saturday after two leading intellectuals were blocked
from entering the city to address a nationwide conference of the
Office to Foster Unity (OFU), the largest student group backing
President Mohammad Khatami's reform programs.
</P>
<P>
The incident touched off days of violence between supporters of
the pro-reform group and the country's conservative radicals. A
policeman was killed and many people, including Governor-General of
Lorestan Norollah Abedi, were wounded in violent attacks by the
conservative assailants.
</P>
<P>
President Khatami's reformist allies condemned the "calculated"
and "well-organized" attacks which, they said, aimed to weaken the
authority of the government.
</P>
<P>
They urged the judiciary authorities to make a rapid probe into
the incidents and bring the trouble-makers, who were also
responsible for many previous anti-reform riots, to justice.
</P>
<P>
The OFU students, who were forced to cut short the conference,
claimed on Tuesday that some "known elements" were involved in
beating the students and wounding more than 100 of them.
</P>
<P>
In an implicit way, they were referring to the pro-conservative
armed Basij (voluntary Islamic militia) and the elite Islamic
Revolution Guards Corps, who are under direct control of the
supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
The recent attacks marked the start of a new wave of suppression
and obstruction by the conservatives to confront the reformist
movement, which has been fostered by President Khatami since his
election in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The reformist movement also managed to end the long-time
conservative control of the Majlis (parliament) in February's
election.
</P>
<P>
However, despite their loss of the executive and legislative
branches of the system, the conservatives still control most of the
other important state organs, including the judiciary, the armed
forces and state-run radio and televisions.
</P>
<P>
In the past few months, the conservative judiciary has ordered
to close more than 20 pro-reform papers and journals and imprisoned
a number of reformist figures on charges of violating Islamic
principles and advocating American-style reforms.
</P>
<P>
Conservative radicals, particularly members of the Ansar-e
Hezbollah (Friends of God Party) and the Basij, have frequently
launched violent attacks on pro-reform allies and beat students and
people attending the reformist rallies.
</P>
<P>
In face of the powerful conservative offensive, President
Khatami and his reformist allies have urged the reformist movement
to exercise restraint in case the situation gets out of control,
which is clearly to the benefit of the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
However, with the 2001 presidential election drawing near and
President Khatami's recent announcement that he will seek a second
term, the conservatives are expected to exert more and more
pressures on the reformers to avoid another humiliating defeat.
</P>
</TEXT>
