<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Removes View-Obstructed Buildings Around Famous Temple </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, August 31 (Xinhua) -- China recently started to
remove a number of buildings believed to have negatively
influenced the natural landscape around the famous Shaolin Temple,
known as the birthplace of Chinese Kung Fu.
</P>
<P>
Some 270 buildings will be removed in the coming month, an
official source said.
</P>
<P>
"The temple and its surrounding areas will take on a new look
to welcome visitors from all over the world by October 1, China's
National Day and a golden tourism season," the source said.
</P>
<P>
More trees will be planted in the area and the management of
commercial and entertainment venues will be improved, an official
noted," adding that "We will also build a Shaolin Kung Fu Museum
near the temple."
</P>
<P>
Shaolin Temple, which attracts 2 million visitors a year, was
first built some 1,500 years ago. It became famous literally
overnight when the movie "Shaolin Temple" first hit the screen
some 20 years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
