<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, August 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Rolls-Royce announced Wednesday that six European
aerospace companies have signed a Memorandum of Agreement to
collaborate on the promotion of a three-shaft turboprop engine.
</P>
<P>
The three-shaft Trent architecture and an M88 derived core will
be proposed for the future A400M military transport aircraft,
according to the announcement. (Rolls-Royce-Memorandum)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Belgian officials said Wednesday that the
government is due to agree to a radical personal tax-cut package
that could see an overall tax bill reduction of more than 130
billion Belgian francs (2.88 billion U.S. dollars) within three
years.
</P>
<P>
The new tax plan, proposed by Belgian Finance Minister Didier
Reynders, was presented to key cabinet members Tuesday and will be
put to the full cabinet Friday for approval. (Belgium-Tax-Cut)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Visiting Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez said
Wednesday that his country will defend the stability of the oil
price in the meeting of Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC), in Caracas next month.
</P>
<P>
He said at a press conference that the rise of crude price in
recent months was not benefiting Venezuela, where 80 percent of
its economy was tied to the sale of oil, because the products are
overpriced in some importing countries, such as the United States,
Germany, Italy and Britain. (Venezuela-Oil Price)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF has vowed again
to continue supporting Indonesia despite signs that Indonesia's
new chief economic minister wanted some changes in the IMF-
sponsored economic reform program.
</P>
<P>
The pledge was expressed by IMF Asia Pacific deputy director
Anoop Singh Wednesday after a meeting with Coordinating Minister
for Economic Affairs Rizal Ramli here, the Jakarta Post daily
reported Thursday. (Indonesia-IMF)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- Eleven more state-owned enterprises of four
ministries in Myanmar will be sold through competitive bidding,
official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises to be auctioned include one plot and two
warehouses of the Ministry of Hotels and Tourism, six cinemas of
the Ministry of Information, one timber shop of the Ministry of
Forestry and one ice factory of the Ministry of Livestock and
Fishery.(Myanmar-Privatization)  
