<HEADLINE> Lankan President Charges Opposition Leader Aware Of Assassination  Attempt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga has charged that main opposition leader Ranil
Wickremesinghe was aware of details of the assassination attempt
on her life by a Tamil Tiger suicide bomber during last December
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Uva Province convention of her Sri Lanka Freedom
Party on Wednesday, Kumaratunga challenged the opposition United
National Party (UNP) leader Ranil to deny this allegation publicly
and clear his name, if the allegation was false.
</P>
<P>
She further charged that a UNP Parliament Member was also
involved in the conspiracy and had constant talks with the
leadership of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) to
commit this crime.
</P>
<P>
She said she escaped death on that occasion but still risked
her life to assure a peaceful Sri Lanka for future generations
which she was committed to till peace was achieved in her country.
</P>
<P>
She added that the LTTE never wanted peace and the UNP had
aligned itself with them to eliminate ruling People's Alliance (PA)
leadership.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga said that the PA would never do anything secretly
nor would they discuss or enter into any negotiation till the LTTE
laid down their arms.
</P>
<P>
She pledged to destroy terrorism and implement the political
solution to end the war and achieve lasting peace. She hoped the
people would give her the required two third majority in the
Parliament to fulfill that task.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga narrowly escaped an assassination attempt but lost
her vision in her right eye on December 18 last year when a LTTE
woman suicide bomber struck after an election rally in Town Hall.
</P>
<P>
LTTE has been fighting a 17-year bloody war against government
forces in the north and east of the country in an attempt to
create an independent Tamil state. Numbers of high-ranking
government officials have been targeted on top of their lists.
</P>
</TEXT>
