<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laos' GDP Up 5.9% in First 10 Months Of Current Fiscal Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 31 (Xinhua)-- Laos' Gross Domestic Product (GDP)
increased 5.9% in the first 10 months of the current fiscal year
to be ended on September 30, on a year-on-year basis, surpassing
the official target of 5%, said a report reaching here Thursday
from the official Laos News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The data was presented at a monthly meeting of the Lao
government late August, under the chairmanship of Prime Minister
Sisavath Keobounphanh, it said.
</P>
<P>
The growth rates in the main GDP sectors of agricultural and
forestry, industry and handicraft, and services during the first
10 months were 4.4%, 7.3% and 6.4%, respectively, it stated.
</P>
<P>
During the period, it said, exports were valued at 323 million
U.S.dollars and imports at 540 million dollars, causing a trade
deficit of 217 million dollars, or 12% of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Foreign grants worth 272 million dollars and foreign loans
worth 72 million dollars were received during the 10 months.
</P>
<P>
The government targets GDP growth of 6% to 6.5% in next fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
Business sources in Thailand said as the Lao economy recovering,
Lao currency kip is now steady, the exchange rate is 7,990 kips to
one dollar in late August, dipping slightly from 7,790 in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
Kip had fallen below 10,000 to the dollar late last year, due
to the collapse in investment and trade from neighboring Thailand
following its financial crisis in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
