<HEADLINE> IMF Pledges to Continue Supporting Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF has vowed again to continue supporting Indonesia despite
signs that Indonesia's new chief economic minister wanted some
changes in the IMF-sponsored economic reform program.
</P>
<P>
The pledge was expressed by IMF Asia Pacific deputy director
Anoop Singh Wednesday after a meeting with Coordinating Minister
for Economic Affairs Rizal Ramli here, the Jakarta Post daily
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"I'm here to convey a message that the IMF is committed to
strongly support Indonesia, there is no doubt about it," said
Singh, adding that his meeting with Rizal focused on ways to
increase "the government ownership of the program."
</P>
<P>
The IMF promised in January this year 5 billion U.S. dollars to
support Indonesia's economic recovery. So far, it has disbursed
some 700 million U.S. dollars to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The previous economic ministers said in July that the IMF was
expected to disburse another 400 million U.S. dollars in late
August.
</P>
<P>
However, since his appointment as the top economic minister,
Rizal has said that he wanted to make some changes in the roles of
the IMF and other multilateral lending institutions in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Rizal has yet to disclose what exactly was on his mind, but he
said recently that the IMF should not be too involved in the
development of economic sectors such as the agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
The core competence of the IMF was in monetary stability, noted
Rizal who has been one of the strongest critics of the IMF reform
program in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
