<HEADLINE> Two German Airmen Killed in Jet Crash in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Two German crew members were
killed Wednesday in a jet crash in Labrador, northeastern Canada.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian search and rescue center received an emergency
signal beacon around 10 a.m. (1400 GMT), after the pilot and
navigator of the Tornado aircraft were reported missing from NATO
training exercises, according to the Canadian military.
</P>
<P>
"The first we knew was when the electronic emergency locator
transmitter went off," said Canadian Forces spokesman Dave Murault.
</P>
<P>
Rescue aircraft were sent to the crash site and found smoke
coming from a hilly, wooded area about 177 kilometers south of
Goose Bay, Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
Murault said the rescuers "have confirmed the two aircrew are
dead."
</P>
<P>
For many years, German, British, Italian and Dutch military
aircraft have trained in Goose Bay because of its natural
conditions for low-level tactical flying exercises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
