<HEADLINE> Sydney Hotel Workers Rally Against Olympic Raffle Ticket Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Around 60 workers rallied
outside the Inter-Continental hotel in Sydney Thursday to protest
against an offer of raffle tickets instead of a cash bonus for
extra work during the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Chanting "more pay" and "the Intercon sucks", the workers
raffled off three matchbox cars in protest at the five-star hotel'
s offer.
</P>
<P>
The Liquor, Hospitality and Miscellaneous Workers Union (LHMU)
said the workers were appalled by the offer from hotel management.
</P>
<P>
The union is asking all Sydney hotels to pay workers a 550-
Australian dollar (324.5 U.S. dollars) Olympic allowance to work
during the Games.
</P>
<P>
The protest was peaceful but two police did ask the protesters
to keep the streets clear.
</P>
<P>
LHMU Assistant Secretary Mark Boyd said earlier the Olympic
bonus incentive included a ticket in the car raffle and a 50-
Australian dollar (29.5 U.S. dollars) gift voucher for full time
staff.
</P>
<P>
Casual staff have been excluded from the gift voucher offer, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The union said the Inter-Continental was charging 2,000
Australian dollars (1,180 U.S.dollars) a night and would be home
during the Games to senior executives, producers and journalists
from American media giant NBC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
