<HEADLINE> Lazio's Zenden Deal Falls Through </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Barcelona's Dutch star Boudewijn
Zenden will not be playing for Italian champions Lazio this season,
Lazio Chairman Sergio Cragnotti said Wednesday, confirming press
reports that the deal had fallen through at the last moment.
</P>
<P>
"It's a pity, I was hoping (to get Zenden)," Cragnotti said,
adding that he was optimistic and felt let down, just like (Lazio
coach Sven Goran) Eriksson.
</P>
<P>
Cragnotti said Barcelona coach Serra Ferrer had decided to halt
the deal early Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Barcelona now considers Zenden "unsellable," Cragnotti said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Lazio sources said Zenden had agreed to sign for
Lazio for around 24 billion lire (about 12 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Zenden, who shone with the Dutch side at this summer's European
Championships, would have received 4.4 billion lire net for four
years, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Lazio badly wanted Zenden to replace Portuguese player Sergio
Conceicao, who joined Parma in the summer's biggest package deal,
the world record 50 million U.S. dollars signing of Argentinian
striker Hernan Crespo.
</P>
<P>
As well as Conceicao and cash, Parma also got non-stop
Argentinian midfielder Mattias Almeyda.
</P>
<P>
Zenden would have completed a glittering front line, playing
alongside Crespo and his fellow Argentine Claudio Lopez, another
summer signing from Valencia.
</P>
<P>
Lazio also has Chilean ace Marcelo "The Matador" Salas, a
recent match-winner against Brazil. 
