<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qinhuangdao, Top Fruits Distributing Center in N. China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINHUANGDAO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Qinhuangdao, a port city in
north China's Hebei Province, has become the largest international
distribution and transfer center for fruits in north China,
according to Mayor Ning Jinbiao.
</P>
<P>
According to Ning, fresh fruits are transported via the
Qinhuangdao Port from Americas and Southeast Asia to Mongolia,
Russia, Middle Asia and central and western parts of China, and
vice versa.
</P>
<P>
The city is also the country's largest banana distributing hub.
"In 1999, Qinhuangdao imported 240,000 tons of bananas, accounting
for 52 percent of the country's total," the official said.
</P>
<P>
Qinhuangdao, 278 kilometers east of Beijing, is also a major
grain importer in China. "The corn exports stood at 1 million tons
last year, ranking second in China," he said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, China plans to build Qinhuangdao Port into a big
trading and transport center for minerals and other industrial
materials, according to the mayor.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's "Graybeard Internet Users" Growing: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The number of Chinese "graybeard
Internet users" who are above 50 years old has increased to 140,
000, a latest survey indicates.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by Chinese Internet Information Center,
shows that the number of internet users of this age group has
increased by 55 percent in the past six months, accounting for 1.6
percent of the total number of Chinese Internet users.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that 6 percent of Chinese Internet users
in cities are below 18 years old and 4 percent are above 55.
</P>
<P>
The report based on this survey said, "Surfing on the Internet
has become a sweeping vogue in China."
</P>
<P>
In a test which required the participants to spend 72 hours
with Internet as their sole connection to the outside world, the
oldest applicants were, 73, from Beijing , and 67, from Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
However, some experts pointed out that the number of graybeard
Internet-users are still insignificant compared with 126 million
senior citizens in China.
</P>
<P>
Min Dahong, an scholar at the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, admitted that no influential website is able to provide
comprehensive service for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the number of Chinese Internet users has
reached 11 million, and the figure would exceed 30 million by the
year 2003.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
