<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Discovered 2,800-Year-Old Gingko Tree </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINHUANGDAO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- An ancient gingko tree,
believed to be 2,800 years old, has been discovered in a village
in Qinhuangdao of north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
The trunk of the tree has a perimeter of over four meters, and
its crown covers about 0.07 hectare.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yuntao, an expert on ancient trees, said that it was the
suitable geological position, weather and soil that enabled the
tree to survive so many years.
</P>
<P>
He also attributed the tree's survival to the strong protection
consciousness of local people.
</P>
<P>
The gingko is a dioecious plant species -- comes in both sexes -
- which survived the glacial period over 2 million years ago in
China.
</P>
<P>
The tree is also known as the "longevity tree" because it can
live up to 1,000 years. Gingkoes are highly valued for their
medicinal properties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Improved Ticket to Ride for Tourists: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- China's top tourism
administration and several provincial tourism departments have
signed an agreement with 65 travel services to guarantee the
rights and interests of Chinese mainland tourists in Singapore,
Malaysia, Thailand, Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
He Guangwei, director of China National Tourism Administration,
said the tourism market and travel agencies would be inspected
regularly to eliminate any malpractice, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We must take effective measures to regulate the tourism market
of Chinese outbound tour groups as soon as possible," He said.
</P>
<P>
China has become one of the top tourism generating countries in
Asia since its opening up in 1978; the number of Chinese going
overseas hit 9.23 million last year.
</P>
<P>
Previously, travel agencies at home and abroad joined to offer
extremely low charges as a way of attracting tourists. To try to
make up for these losses, travel agencies in the destination
countries and regions urged tourists to spend their money in
shopping centers and sought commission from retailers. Tourists
would eventually find their costs were much higher than usual.
</P>
<P>
Such practices by travel agencies "not only seriously infringed
the tourists' rights and interests, but also damaged tourism and
the interests of law-abiding travel services," said Wang Suqi,
manager of Outbound Tour for the Chinese Citizen Department of
China International Travel Service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
