<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province Sets Up First Geology Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 31 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province
recently set up its first geological park, focusing on seashore
volcano landscape and ancient forest ruins with over 10,000 years
of history.
</P>
<P>
The park is located in Zhangpu County of Zhangzhou, where a 22
million-year-old seabed crater, believed to be the only one of its
kind in the world, is still well preserved.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization has decided to choose the first group of the world's
best geological parks starting from the year 2003, and China will
do a similar thing in 2002.
</P>
<P>
"With rich geological landscapes, we are confident we will be
able to compete with other parks after two or three years of
effort," a park manager said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
