<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Rebels Make New Demand for Hostage Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leonean rebel group, The
West Side Boys, which is currently holding seven hostages, has put
forward new demands following the  earlier release of five of its
captives, according to reports reaching here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the rebel group Colonel Cambodia was quoted as
saying in Freetown, the capital of the war-torn west African
country, that the rebels wanted a review of the Lome Peace Accord,
their reintegration into the government army as well as the
release of their supporters from jail.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said their captives were well treated and being
properly fed and provided with adequate medicine and shelter,
adding that the rest would not be released until their new demands
were met.
</P>
<P>
Twelve soldiers including 11 Britons and one Sierra Leonean
were taken hostage by the West Side Boys last Friday when they
were patrolling along the Freetown-Masiaka highway.
</P>
<P>
Following the abduction of the soldiers, the rebel group had
demanded food, medicine and the release of one of their leaders in
return for the release of the hostage.
</P>
<P>
Five British soldiers were released on Wednesday by the
abductors and returned safely to their barracks in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations for the release of the remaining soldiers were
reportedly under way among the Sierra Leonean government, the
United Nations Mission in Sierra Leone, the British and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
However, no response was yet available to the new demands of
the rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
