<HEADLINE> High Baby Mortality Rate Reported in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian health officials have
decried the high baby mortality rate in the country, where five
out of every 100 babies die yearly under the age of five.
</P>
<P>
The high mortality rate was attributed to preventable childhood
diseases and poor health care delivery, the News Agency of Nigeria
Thursday quoted the officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
Grace Delano, executive director of the Association for
Reproductive and Family Health, said that the government should
take practical measures to check the increasing baby mortality
rate through improved education and sound technology.
</P>
<P>
"The earlier we act the better for our future," Delano said at
an academic workshop in the southwestern city of Ibadan.
</P>
<P>
Describing nurses and midwives as the bedrock of the primary
health care system, Delano said it was necessary to continuously
educate them and improve their skills and competence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
