<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traffic on Move as French Protests End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- British holidaymakers began
arriving home Thursday after French fishermen who were angry at
rising fuel prices called off their two-day blockade.
</P>
<P>
Tension between the protesters and holidaymakers had reached
near the boiling point at ports around the French coast before the
blockade was called off. The fishermen ended their protests after
the French government agreed to cut social security payments in
compensation.
</P>
<P>
Furious British tourists, some of whom had been stranded for
more than 36 hours, lost their tempers as they faced the prospect
of another night sleeping in their cars.
</P>
<P>
Lorries which had blocked the tunnel entrance outside Calais
were moved, as were the fishing boats blocking the port entrance.
</P>
<P>
Stranded holidaymakers were allowed through all eight lanes of
the Eurotunnel terminal within 20 minutes of the blockade being
lifted and the threats of violence subsided.
</P>
<P>
Protest leaders said they were "satisfied" with the outcome of
talks with French Agriculture Minister Jean Glavany but British
holidaymakers returning home were not so happy.
</P>
<P>
British Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott told BBC that a
long-term strategy should be introduced to prevent the British
being affected by "what is essentially a French problem."
</P>
<P>
"It is totally unacceptable that Britain could be held to
ransom in this kind of blockade raising out of a dispute in France,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Prescott called on the EU Transport Commissioner Loyola de
Palacio to arrange an urgent meeting with UK Transport Minister
Lord Macdonald to discuss new rules of engagement to handle future
disputes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
