<HEADLINE> Brazil, Venezuela to Promote Mercosur-CAN Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso and his Venezuelan counterpart, Hugo Chavez,
Thursday agreed to promote integration between the Southern Common
Market (Mercosur) and the Andean Community of Nations (CAN) in
view of establishing a free trade area between the two blocs.
</P>
<P>
This was made known Thursday in a joint communique published by
Brazil's Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
President Chavez arrived one day before the start of the South
American Summit to pay a working visit to Brazil. He got together
with his Brazilian counterpart to examine the most important
aspects of the bilateral agenda and maintain a dialogue on
ententes between Mercosur and CAN.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian leader, in the capacity of president in turn of
Mercosur, briefed his Venezuelan counterpart on the reinitiation
of negotiations with CAN in view of signing an accord to regulate
trade relations between both blocs on December 31, 2001.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the two presidents agreed to carry out
necessary coordination, together with the partners of each group,
in order to define a date, in coming October, for the start of
negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
