<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Refuses Third Party Mediation on Hostage Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Thursday
ruled out mediation by a third party to help release a U.S.
hostage held by Muslim rebels in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"We're not interested in third-party mediation, we're not
seeking mediation efforts by third countries," State Department
Richard Boucher said, responding to a question that whether the U.
S. accepts the help offered by Libya.
</P>
<P>
Boucher said U.S. officials had close contact with the
Philippine government which is in charge of the effort to win the
release of Jeffrey Schilling, 24, who has been held by Abu Sayyaf
rebels on the remote Philippine island of Jolo since Monday.
</P>
<P>
Boucher urged the Abu Sayyaf group to release Schilling on the
grounds that he had "long-term health problems" and needed
prescription medication.
</P>
<P>
Refusing to specify Schilling's illness, the spokesman said
that "we see no advantage to continuing to hold Mr. Schilling. And
for humanitarian reasons alone, we think he should be released
quickly and safely."
</P>
<P>
Libya, which had earlier help secure the release of six of a
group of western and Philippine hostages held by Abu Sayyaf, said
on Tuesday that it would also be prepared to work for Schilling's
release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
