<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rise Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks rose sharply
Thursday as a new report showing a slowdown in the U.S. economy
encouraged investors to enter the market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 112.09 at 11,215.10
points, recovering all the losses of 112.09 points Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 102.54 at 4,206.35 and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 15.09 at 1,517.68.
</P>
<P>
Stock rose after the Commerce Department reported that new
orders to U.S. factories plunged by a record 7.5 percent in July.
The new data showed that the U.S. economy is slowing and inflation
remains tame after six hikes in interest rates in the past 14
months.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve decided to leave rates unchanged at a
monetary policy meeting last week and the new report of the
slowing economy would prompt the central bank to end the current
tightening cycle.
</P>
<P>
The market was also buoyed by Wednesday's merger announcement.
Credit Suisse First Boston announced that it was acquiring
Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette for 11.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
J.P. Morgan rose sharply, leading the Dow index higher.
</P>
<P>
In the tech sector, computer, Internet and telecom issues rose,
pushing the Nasdaq composite higher. Among them were Intel, Dell
computer, Microsoft and Gateway.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 4.07 at 674.53 and the American Stock
Exchange index rose 9.26 at 943.48. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 5.56 at 537.89.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,727 up, 1,158 down and 509
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 1.05 billion shares from 813.26
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
