<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Drug Use Declines in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Illegal drug use among teen-
agers continue to fall in the United States for a second year, a
government survey said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the survey, 9 percent of 12-to-17-year-olds questioned said
they had used an illegal drug such as marijuana or heroin within
the previous month, down from 9.9 percent in 1998, and 11.4
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The National Household Survey on Drug Abuse was released by
Barry McCaffrey, President Clinton's drug policy adviser, and
Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala.
</P>
<P>
"It's going to go down again for sure next year," McCaffrey
said. "These prevention and education programs are working."
</P>
<P>
However, the survey showed that drug use among young adults of
18-to-25-year-olds climbed from 14.7 percent in 1997 to 18.8
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
"None of us can afford to let down our guard in the fight
against drug, tobacco and alcohol abuse, especially when it comes
to our children," President Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He urged Congress to fund his administration's substance abuse
and treatment programs when it returns next week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
