<DOCNO> XIE20000831.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Says Forces Maybe Not Ready for Two Wars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. armed forces are
mostly ready to perform wartime missions, but if the country had
to fight two major wars at the same time, it would run a high risk
of increased casualties because of shortfalls in logistic support,
the Pentagon said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Most major combat and support forces are ready to meet
assigned taskings under this scenario (two wars at the same time),
although there are force readiness and capability shortfalls that
increase risk in executing operations," the Pentagon said in a
periodical assessment report to the Congress.
</P>
<P>
The term "risk" in this context means the risk of not meeting
field commanders' timetables for moving forces to a theater of war
and executing the war plan, the Associated Press said. It does not
mean the risk of failing to win the war, but rather the risk that
longer timelines for starting combat operations would mean high U.
S. casualties.
</P>
<P>
The assessment, required by the Congress every three months,
also said the U.S. military services are facing training problems,
personnel shortages and aging equipment. Even so, it concluded
that "America's armed forces remain capable of executing" the
military strategy of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
The report comes amid growing debate between the presidential
campaigns of Vice President Al Gore and Texas Governor George W.
Bush about whether the Clinton administration has sapped the
strength of the U.S. military. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
